(1195, 5, '2014-11-18 21:27:02', '2014-11-18 21:27:02', 'TheÂ Brevard Oyster Gardening project, launched by Brevard Zoo in partnership with the Brevard County Natural Resources Management Office, is encouraging the community to get involved with the process of repairing damages to the lagoon. Inspired by the oyster reef restoration work that Brevard Zoo has been doing with UCF in Mosquito Lagoon, the Oyster Gardening Project has expanded reef restoration intoÂ Brevard Countyâs portion of theÂ Indian River Lagoon by first identifying areas with high rates of oyster survivability and recruitment that are good candidate locations for a future reef restoration project. Oysters grown through the Oyster Gardening program have then been used to populate Brevard County restoration reefs, starting with the very first reefs built in the fall of 2014â¦\r\n\r\n<img class="alignnone  wp-image-716" alt="Home7" src="http://brevardoystergardens.org/wp-content/uploads/2014/04/Home7.jpg" width="974" height="773" />\r\n\r\nIn order to grow oysters and collect the necessary data, the Brevard County Commissioners funded the project with $150,000 to supply a small staff and provide the necessary equipment to train volunteers in Brevard County to become âoyster gardeners.â The project relies almost entirely onÂ <a href="https://mapalist.com/Public/pm.aspx?mapid=435233" target="_blank">these volunteers</a>Â living along the shores of the Indian River Lagoon who agree to hang oyster habitats from their docks and then care for and monitor their oysters to collect data on the growth, survivability, and recruitment of oysters in their area, all of which gets entered into a database on a weekly basis for a period of about six Â months.\r\n\r\n<img class="alignnone  wp-image-596" alt="Oysters_Kiwanis Park 36" src="http://brevardoystergardens.org/wp-content/uploads/2014/03/Oysters_Kiwanis-Park-361.jpg" width="3312" height="2704" />\r\n\r\nOyster gardeners first attend a special workshop where they learn all the details of the program and build their own oyster habitats. Later, they receive oyster shells covered with live spat (juvenile oysters), which they place into their habitats and then deploy from their docks, beginning the care and data collection process. To ensure the greatest probability of success, the oyster spat used in the Oyster Gardening project are spawned from a local brood stock near Sebastian, FL. Their spawning takes place at the Florida Oceanographic Society, in a hatchery dedicated to the reproduction of the Eastern Oyster. Using a local population of oysters from Brevard County to parent these oyster spat will keep future generations of oysters in restored populations genetically similar to those that once made up the areaâs original population.\r\n\r\n[gallery columns="5" link="file" ids="656,658,654,603,1076"]', 'Oyster Gardening Program', '', 'inherit', 'closed', 'open', '', '899-revision-v1', '', '', '2014-11-18 21:27:02', '2014-11-18 21:27:02', '', 899, 'http://brevardoystergardens.org/899-revision-v1/', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
(551, 3, '2014-04-03 20:33:44', '2014-04-03 20:33:44', '<a href="http://darrengriffith.net/wp/wp-content/uploads/2014/03/why1.png"><img class="alignnone size-medium wp-image-141" alt="why1" src="http://darrengriffith.net/wp/wp-content/uploads/2014/03/why1-300x158.png" width="300" height="158" /></a>\n\n&nbsp;\n\nDid you know oysters can actually swim for the first two weeks of their lives? Adult oysters release their gametes into the water, where they join and create a fertilized egg that will become a free-swimming larvae. For the next two weeks, this oyster larvae is traveling through the Indian River Lagoon looking for a place to live. This is a very important decision because after these two weeks, the oysters are stationary and they will stay in the same location for the rest of their lives.\n\n<a href="http://darrengriffith.net/wp/wp-content/uploads/2014/03/why2.jpg"><img class="alignnone size-medium wp-image-142" alt="why2" src="http://darrengriffith.net/wp/wp-content/uploads/2014/03/why2-300x225.jpg" width="300" height="225" /></a>\n\n<a href="http://darrengriffith.net/wp/wp-content/uploads/2014/03/why2.jpg"><a href="http://darrengriffith.net/wp/wp-content/uploads/2014/03/why3.jpg"><img class="alignnone size-medium wp-image-143" alt="why3" src="http://darrengriffith.net/wp/wp-content/uploads/2014/03/why3-300x188.jpg" width="300" height="188" /></a></a>\n\nOysters are gregarious species, meaning they prefer to live among other oysters. As this free-swimming larvae is floating through the lagoon, sometimes for miles, they are looking for other oysters to settle with. They also require a hard substrate to attach to, where they can grow and build their shell composed of calcium. The average life span of the Eastern Oyster, <i>Crassostrea virginica</i>, is approximately 20 years.', 'Why Oysters?', '', 'inherit', 'open', 'open', '', '140-revision-v1', '', '', '2014-04-03 20:33:44', '2014-04-03 20:33:44', '', 140, 'http://brevardoystergardens.org/?p=551', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
(1147, 5, '2014-10-02 15:57:55', '2014-10-02 15:57:55', '&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<img class="alignnone size-full wp-image-916" alt="bz logo" src="http://brevardoystergardens.org/wp-content/uploads/2014/03/bz-logo.jpeg" width="358" height="141" />\r\n\r\n<a href="http://www.brevardzoo.org/" target="_blank">Brevard Zoo</a>Â is a small zoo that does big things. We focus on providing top quality care for our animals, offering unique opportunities for guests to experience nature both on- and off-site, and actively participating with Brevard County Public Schools to develop education programs that serve diverse audiences with authentic learning. Our mission is âWildlife Conservation through Education and Participation,â and the Brevard Oyster Restoration project team at Brevard Zoo actively follows this mission through the Oyster Mats and Oyster Gardening programs by working directly with the community to actively restore the Indian River Lagoon. Brevard Zoo houses all of the staff and supplies for each project.<b>Â </b>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Â OYSTER GARDENING PARTNERS</strong>\r\n\r\n<img class="alignnone size-medium wp-image-1070" alt="" src="http://brevardoystergardens.org/wp-content/uploads/2014/03/county-logo300-300x167.png" width="300" height="167" />\r\n\r\nTheÂ <a href="http://www.brevardcounty.us/NaturalResources" target="_blank">Brevard County Natural Resources Management Department</a>, along with the County Commissioners, provided $150,000 to fund the Oyster Gardening project. That money has been used to purchase supplies for hundreds of oyster gardeners in Brevard County and hire a small staff to lead the project. The county is actively involved in educating the public about the issues facing the Indian River Lagoon and the steps being taken within our community to provide solutions.\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<img class="alignnone size-full wp-image-919" alt="" src="http://brevardoystergardens.org/wp-content/uploads/2014/03/Eastern_Florida_State_College_Logo.png" width="357" height="200" />\r\n\r\nThe <a href="http://www.easternflorida.edu/" target="_blank">Eastern Florida State College</a> Environmental Club of the Melbourne Campus seeks to promote environmental stewardship through the service of its members, educate the public on the importance of maintaining a healthy ecosystem through community outreach, and support the Eastern Florida State College Melbourne Campus in its efforts to pursue and maintain a sustainable environment. The club is fulfilling this mission statement through the countless hours of preparation work its members do for oyster gardening workshops, including cutting wire to create oyster habitats.\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<img class="alignnone  wp-image-920" alt="" src="http://brevardoystergardens.org/wp-content/uploads/2014/03/UF_Logo.jpg" width="502" height="153" />\r\nThe <a href="http://brevard.ifas.ufl.edu" target="_blank">University Of Florida IFAS</a> Extension Brevard County is partnering with Brevard County and Brevard Zoo to teach waterfront property owners about how to get involved with the Oyster Gardening program. Meanwhile, the <a href="http://www.flseagrant.org/" target="_blank">Florida Sea Grant</a> Extension agent for Brevard County provides educational opportunities and university research-based information on a variety of topics and issues to the citizens of Brevard County.\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<img class="alignnone  wp-image-921" alt="" src="http://brevardoystergardens.org/wp-content/uploads/2014/03/Screen-Shot-2014-07-10-at-10.20.06-AM.png" width="563" height="163" />\r\n\r\n<a href="http://www.modusoperandi.com/" target="_blank">Modus Operandi</a>Â is high-tech software company specializing in delivering technology that helps organizations discover the hidden patterns locked in their data.\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<b>Â OYSTER MATS PARTNERS</b>\r\n\r\n<img class="alignnone  wp-image-918" alt="" src="http://brevardoystergardens.org/wp-content/uploads/2014/03/DUCF36__55990.1360004520.1280.1280.jpg" width="253" height="253" />\r\n\r\nUse of Oyster Mats for oyster reef restoration was pioneered by <a href="http://biology.cos.ucf.edu/faculty/linda-walters/" target="_blank">Dr. Linda Walters</a>, of the <a href="http://www.ucf.edu/" target="_blank">University of Central Florida</a>, and has proven to be a successful scientific-based restoration technique.Â Together, UCF and Brevard Zoo deploy these mats into Mosquito Lagoon at designated restoration sites and continue to monitor their progress through research and data collection. In addition to oyster mat restoration, University of Central Florida is leading living shoreline stabilization efforts in Canaveral National Seashore and aiming to <a href="http://today.ucf.edu/ucf-app-aims-prevent-boat-mishaps-protect-mosquito-lagoon/" target="_blank">reduce boating collisions</a> with oyster reefs.\r\n\r\n<a href="http://brevardoystergardens.org/wp-content/uploads/2014/03/ccalogo3x3.jpg"><img class="alignnone  wp-image-1141" alt="ccalogo3x3" src="http://brevardoystergardens.org/wp-content/uploads/2014/03/ccalogo3x3.jpg" width="318" height="330" /></a>\r\n\r\nThe Coastal Conservation Association seeks to advise and educate the public on the conservation of marine resources, with the objective of ensuring the future availability for the benefit and enjoyment of the general public. The Orlando Chapter of CCA is a Â powerhouse for the Oyster Mats program, providing boats and volunteers to help out with reef-building efforts each summer.\r\n\r\n<a href="http://brevardoystergardens.org/wp-content/uploads/2014/03/sjrwmd.png"><img class="alignnone  wp-image-1142" alt="sjrwmd" src="http://brevardoystergardens.org/wp-content/uploads/2014/03/sjrwmd.png" width="280" height="280" /></a>\r\n\r\nThe St. Johns River Water Management District is responsible for managing groudwater and surface water resources for all or part of 18 counties in northeast and east-central Florida, including Brevard County and the Indian River Lagoon. The SJRWMD provides funding for the Oyster Mats project through sales of their special Indian River Lagoon license plate, also known as the "snook tag." 100 percent of proceeds from sales of the tag go directly to restoration and education efforts related to the lagoon.\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<a href="http://brevardoystergardens.org/wp-content/uploads/2014/03/DWCF-LogoType-4C.jpg"><img class="alignnone  wp-image-1143" alt="DWCF Logo Mark 4C" src="http://brevardoystergardens.org/wp-content/uploads/2014/03/DWCF-LogoType-4C.jpg" width="415" height="216" /></a>\r\n\r\nDisney Worldwide Conservation Fund is a key pillar in Disney''s efforts to protect the planet and help kids develop lifelong conservation values. DWCF provides grant support for the Oyster Mats program and many other projects around the world to support the study of wildlife, the protection of habitats, the development of community conservation and education programs, and experiences that connect kids to nature.\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<a href="http://brevardoystergardens.org/wp-content/uploads/2014/03/NOAA-Transparent-Logo.png"><img class="alignnone  wp-image-1144" alt="NOAA-Transparent-Logo" src="http://brevardoystergardens.org/wp-content/uploads/2014/03/NOAA-Transparent-Logo.png" width="232" height="232" /></a>', 'Our Partners', '', 'inherit', 'closed', 'open', '', '188-revision-v1', '', '', '2014-10-02 15:57:55', '2014-10-02 15:57:55', '', 188, 'http://brevardoystergardens.org/188-revision-v1/', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
(1118, 5, '2014-10-01 17:57:36', '2014-10-01 17:57:36', '<strong>REFERENCE DOCUMENTS</strong>\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li><a href="http://brevardoystergardens.org/wp-content/uploads/2014/07/Version2-_Oyster-Gardening-Presentation_2014.pdf">Oyster Gardening Presentation</a></li>\r\n	<li><a href="http://brevardoystergardens.org/wp-content/uploads/2014/07/Brevard-Oyster-Gardening-Manual_Version-2_2014.pdf">Brevard Oyster Gardening Manual</a></li>\r\n</ul>\r\n(For the above documents, please note that Gardeners who started the program before July 2014 have four habitats instead of two)\r\n\r\n<strong>HABITAT MAINTENANCE TIPS</strong>\r\n\r\n<iframe src="//www.youtube.com/embed/0MoHFOpb3II" height="480" width="853" allowfullscreen="" frameborder="0"></iframe>\r\n\r\n<strong>OYSTER SPAT IDENTIFICATION GUIDES</strong>\r\n\r\nOyster spat 3 weeks post-distribution:\r\n\r\n[gallery link="file" ids="740,739,737"]\r\n\r\nOyster spat 5 weeks post-distribution:\r\n\r\n[gallery link="file" ids="743,742"]\r\n\r\nOyster spat under fouling:\r\n\r\n[gallery columns="4" link="file" ids="843,844,845,849"]\r\n\r\n<strong>OYSTER COHABITANTS IDENTIFICATION GUIDES</strong>\r\n\r\nOyster friends:\r\n\r\n[gallery link="file" columns="5" ids="773,775,727,817,819,820,1115,1116"]\r\n\r\nOyster foes:\r\n\r\n[gallery link="file" columns="5" ids="728,726,725,722,721,768,772,771,770,1106,1108,1111,1112,1113"]\r\n\r\nFound something in your habitat that you don''t see here? Look it up in the Smithsonian Marine Station''sÂ <a href="http://www.sms.si.edu/irlspec/SpeciesImageGallery.htm" target="_blank">Indian River Lagoon Species Database</a>.', 'Oyster Gardening Resources', '', 'inherit', 'closed', 'open', '', '906-revision-v1', '', '', '2014-10-01 17:57:36', '2014-10-01 17:57:36', '', 906, 'http://brevardoystergardens.org/906-revision-v1/', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
