(1121, 5, '2014-10-01 18:09:24', '2014-10-01 18:09:24', '<strong>REFERENCE DOCUMENTS</strong>\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li><a href="http://brevardoystergardens.org/wp-content/uploads/2014/07/Version2-_Oyster-Gardening-Presentation_2014.pdf">Oyster Gardening Presentation</a></li>\r\n	<li><a href="http://brevardoystergardens.org/wp-content/uploads/2014/07/Brevard-Oyster-Gardening-Manual_Version-2_2014.pdf">Brevard Oyster Gardening Manual</a></li>\r\n</ul>\r\n(For the above documents, please note that Gardeners who started the program before July 2014 have four habitats instead of two)\r\n\r\n<strong>HABITAT MAINTENANCE TIPS</strong>\r\n\r\n<iframe src="//www.youtube.com/embed/0MoHFOpb3II" height="480" width="853" allowfullscreen="" frameborder="0"></iframe>\r\n\r\n<strong>OYSTER SPAT IDENTIFICATION GUIDES</strong>\r\n\r\nOyster spat 3 weeks post-distribution:\r\n\r\n[gallery link="file" ids="740,739,737"]\r\n\r\nOyster spat 5 weeks post-distribution:\r\n\r\n[gallery link="file" ids="743,742"]\r\n\r\nOyster spat under fouling:\r\n\r\n[gallery columns="4" link="file" ids="843,844,845,849"]\r\n\r\n<strong>OYSTER COHABITANTS IDENTIFICATION GUIDES</strong>\r\n\r\nOyster friends:\r\n\r\n[gallery link="file" columns="5" ids="773,775,727,817,819,820,1115,1116,1119,1120"]\r\n\r\nOyster foes:\r\n\r\n[gallery link="file" columns="5" ids="728,726,725,722,721,768,772,771,770,1106,1108,1111,1112,1113"]\r\n\r\nFound something in your habitat that you don''t see here? Look it up in the Smithsonian Marine Station''sÂ <a href="http://www.sms.si.edu/irlspec/SpeciesImageGallery.htm" target="_blank">Indian River Lagoon Species Database</a>.', 'Oyster Gardening Resources', '', 'inherit', 'closed', 'open', '', '906-revision-v1', '', '', '2014-10-01 18:09:24', '2014-10-01 18:09:24', '', 906, 'http://brevardoystergardens.org/906-revision-v1/', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
(708, 3, '2014-05-04 22:57:19', '2014-05-04 22:57:19', '<p style="text-align: left;" align="center"><a href="http://brevardoystergardens.org/wp-content/uploads/2014/04/Home1.jpg"><img class="size-full wp-image-709 aligncenter" alt="Home1" src="http://brevardoystergardens.org/wp-content/uploads/2014/04/Home1.jpg" width="1000" height="771" /></a>Stretching 156 miles, the Indian River Lagoon is a one of the most biologically diverse estuaries in the country. Consisting of the Mosquito lagoon and both the Banana and Indian rivers, the majority of the lagoon is located here in Brevard County providing us with a one of a kind treasure. In addition to being economically significant and providing the residents with a great source for recreation, over 4,000 species of animal and plants call the lagoon home. However, in recent years the lagoon has seen an increasing amount of threats to its water quality and biological diversity.</p>\n<p style="text-align: left;" align="center"><a href="http://brevardoystergardens.org/wp-content/uploads/2014/04/Home2.jpg"><img class="alignnone size-full wp-image-710" alt="Home2" src="http://brevardoystergardens.org/wp-content/uploads/2014/04/Home2.jpg" width="462" height="609" /></a></p>\n<p style="text-align: left;" align="center">Once found in abundance along the waterways, but now has disappeared from many portions of the lagoon is the Eastern oyster, <i>Crassotrea virginica</i>. The native oyster population that once thrived here was decimated by a combination of factors; including habitat loss, overharvesting, pollution, reduced water quality, disease, and boat wakes.</p>\n<p style="text-align: left;" align="center"><a href="http://brevardoystergardens.org/wp-content/uploads/2014/04/Home3.jpg"><img class="alignnone size-full wp-image-711" alt="Home3" src="http://brevardoystergardens.org/wp-content/uploads/2014/04/Home3.jpg" width="915" height="427" /></a></p>\n<p style="text-align: left;" align="center">Oysters are an essential part of the Indian River lagoon ecosystem for many reasons. They are a keystone species that numerous other species depend on for food and protection. They are also a gregarious species that clumps together creating natural reefs that help prevent erosion. These reefs provide a nursery for juvenile fishes and other marine species. Oysters are filter feeders, too. This means that they consume the organic material in the lagoon, replacing it with cleaner water. In fact, one average adult oyster can filter up to 50 gallons of water per day. Imagine how many gallons of filtered water this would add up to over the oysterâs 20 year life span! Â Their filtering abilities helps to reduce the amount of algae and muck floating in the river. Improved water clarity and light penetration is especially important for sea grass, another keystone species in the Indian River Lagoon.</p>\n<p style="text-align: left;" align="center"><a href="http://brevardoystergardens.org/wp-content/uploads/2014/04/Home4.jpg"><img class="alignnone size-large wp-image-712" alt="Home4" src="http://brevardoystergardens.org/wp-content/uploads/2014/04/Home4-1024x768.jpg" width="474" height="355" /></a></p>\nBrevard Zoo recognized the importance of using the oysterâs natural ability to filter water as a way to improve the water quality of the Indian River Lagoon. In 2005, Brevard Zoo partnered with the University of Central Florida to restore oyster reefs in Mosquito lagoon.Â  The reefs are created using a quilt-like pattern of oyster mats which was developed by Dr. Linda Walters. Since that time, over 36,000 mats have been made and deployed, establishing 63 new oyster reefs, thanks to the help of over 36,000 volunteers.\n\n<a href="http://brevardoystergardens.org/wp-content/uploads/2014/04/Home5.jpg"><img class="alignnone size-full wp-image-713" alt="Home5" src="http://brevardoystergardens.org/wp-content/uploads/2014/04/Home5.jpg" width="676" height="588" /></a>\n\n<a href="http://brevardoystergardens.org/wp-content/uploads/2014/04/Home61.jpg"><img class="alignnone size-full wp-image-715" alt="Home6" src="http://brevardoystergardens.org/wp-content/uploads/2014/04/Home61.jpg" width="576" height="647" /></a>\n\nRecently, Brevard Zoo has partnered with Brevard County to launch the Oyster Gardening Project. This is a community-based project that relies on the efforts of citizen scientist to collect data on oyster survivability in the Indian River Lagoon.\n\nResidents living along the lagoon volunteer to create oyster habitats and deploy them off of their docks. The habitats are then populated with living oyster spats and are monitored weekly for signs of recruitment and survivability. This data will be used for future large-scale oyster reef restoration projects.\n\n<a href="http://brevardoystergardens.org/wp-content/uploads/2014/04/Home7.jpg"><img class="alignnone size-full wp-image-716" alt="Home7" src="http://brevardoystergardens.org/wp-content/uploads/2014/04/Home7.jpg" width="974" height="773" /></a> <a href="http://brevardoystergardens.org/wp-content/uploads/2014/04/home8.jpg"><img class="alignnone size-large wp-image-717" alt="home8" src="http://brevardoystergardens.org/wp-content/uploads/2014/04/home8.jpg" width="474" height="419" /></a> <a href="http://brevardoystergardens.org/wp-content/uploads/2014/04/Home9.jpg"><img class="alignnone size-large wp-image-718" alt="Home9" src="http://brevardoystergardens.org/wp-content/uploads/2014/04/Home9.jpg" width="474" height="431" /></a>', 'Home', '', 'inherit', 'closed', 'open', '', '587-autosave-v1', '', '', '2014-05-04 22:57:19', '2014-05-04 22:57:19', '', 587, 'http://brevardoystergardens.org/?p=708', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
