(71, 1, '2014-03-30 16:09:10', '2014-03-30 16:09:10', '[gallery columns="5" link="file" ids="1063,1067,1068,1064,1065"]\r\n\r\nOur oyster restoration team collects oyster mats made by volunteers throughout the year. During the summer months, these mats are deployed across Mosquito Lagoon in prepared restoration areas with guidance from the University of Central Floridaâs Dr. Linda Walters, boat support from the Florida Fish &amp; Wildlife Conservation Commission and IRL National Estuary Program, and the hard workÂ ofÂ many dedicated volunteers. Summer is the perfect time of year for this activity, because itâs during oyster spawning season but before barnacle season, giving young oysters enough time to find restored reefs and settle before barnacles appear to compete with them. And once summer draws to a close, completed restoration sites are frequently monitored throughout the year and for years to come.\r\n\r\n<iframe src="https://www.youtube.com/embed/UHyiAtuK7ag" width="853" height="480" frameborder="0" allowfullscreen="allowfullscreen"></iframe>\r\n\r\nThe 2016 oyster mat deployment season in Mosquito Lagoon has concluded.Â However, the Oyster Team still needs your help to build the final reef of the summer in Brevard County. Â To register, please visit the <a href="http://brevardoystergardens.org/volunteer/">volunteer</a> page.', 'Help Deploy Oyster Mats', '', 'publish', 'closed', 'closed', '', 'deployment', '', '', '2016-07-20 21:50:54', '2016-07-20 21:50:54', '', 0, 'http://darrengriffith.net/wp/?page_id=71', 0, 'page', '', 0),
(1194, 5, '2014-11-18 21:25:16', '2014-11-18 21:25:16', 'TheÂ Brevard Oyster Gardening project, launched by Brevard Zoo in partnership with the Brevard County Natural Resources Management Office, is encouraging the community to get involved with the process of repairing damages to the lagoon. Inspired by the oyster reef restoration work that Brevard Zoo has been doing with UCF in Mosquito Lagoon, the Oyster Gardening Project has expanded reef restoration intoÂ Brevard Countyâs portion of theÂ Indian River Lagoon by first identifying areas with high rates of oyster survivability and recruitment that are good candidate locations for a future reef restoration project. Oysters grown through the Oyster Gardening program have then been used to populate Brevard County restoration reefs, starting with the very first reefs built in the fall of 2014...\r\n\r\n<img class="alignnone  wp-image-716" alt="Home7" src="http://brevardoystergardens.org/wp-content/uploads/2014/04/Home7.jpg" width="974" height="773" />\r\n\r\nIn order to grow oysters and collect the necessary data, the Brevard County Commissioners funded the project with $150,000 to supply a small staff and provide the necessary equipment to train volunteers in Brevard County to become âoyster gardeners.â The project relies almost entirely on <a href="https://mapalist.com/Public/pm.aspx?mapid=435233" target="_blank">these volunteers</a> living along the shores of the Indian River Lagoon who agree to hang oyster habitats from their docks and then care for and monitor their oysters to collect data on the growth, survivability, and recruitment of oysters in their area, all of which gets entered into a database on a weekly basis for a period of about six Â months.\r\n\r\n<img class="alignnone  wp-image-596" alt="Oysters_Kiwanis Park 36" src="http://brevardoystergardens.org/wp-content/uploads/2014/03/Oysters_Kiwanis-Park-361.jpg" width="3312" height="2704" />\r\n\r\nOyster gardeners first attend a special workshop where they learn all the details of the program and build their own oyster habitats. Later, they receive oyster shells covered with live spat (juvenile oysters), which they place into their habitats and then deploy from their docks, beginning the care and data collection process. To ensure the greatest probability of success, the oyster spat used in the Oyster Gardening project are spawned from a local brood stock near Sebastian, FL. Their spawning takes place at the Florida Oceanographic Society, in a hatchery dedicated to the reproduction of the Eastern Oyster. Using a local population of oysters from Brevard County to parent our oyster spat will keep future generations of oysters in restored populations genetically similar to those that once made up the areaâs original population.\r\n\r\n[gallery columns="5" link="file" ids="656,658,654,603,1076"]', 'Oyster Gardening Details', '', 'inherit', 'closed', 'open', '', '949-revision-v1', '', '', '2014-11-18 21:25:16', '2014-11-18 21:25:16', '', 949, 'http://brevardoystergardens.org/949-revision-v1/', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
