(1213, 5, '2014-11-20 19:29:49', '2014-11-20 19:29:49', '<iframe src="//www.youtube.com/embed/8s0WGxu_ZL0" height="480" width="853" allowfullscreen="" frameborder="0"></iframe>\r\nHave you seen our new commercial on Brighthouse Networks?\r\n\r\n<a href="http://brevardoystergardens.org/oyster-gardening-workshops/" target="_blank">(Click here if you''re a lagoon-front resident interested in becoming an oyster gardener)</a>\r\n\r\n<a href="http://brevardoystergardens.org/help-make-oyster-mats/" target="_blank">(Click here if you''re interested in making oyster mats)</a>\r\n\r\n<strong>ABOUT BREVARD OYSTER RESTORATION:</strong>\r\n\r\nSpanning 156 miles and five Florida counties, the Indian River Lagoon is one of the most biologically diverse estuaries in the country, providing a home for more than 4,000 species of plants and animals. The vast majority of this waterway, which includes the Mosquito Lagoon area and both the Banana and Indian rivers, is located here in Brevard County, providing our community with a one-of-a-kind ecological and recreational treasure that also has an estimated economic value of $3.7 billon per year.\r\n\r\n<img class="alignnone  wp-image-884" alt="" src="http://brevardoystergardens.org/wp-content/uploads/2014/04/Screen-Shot-2014-07-09-at-4.31.19-PM.png" width="940" height="623" />\r\n\r\nHowever, in recent years, the lagoon has seen increasing threats to its water quality and biological diversity. Continuous inputs of pollution have overloaded the estuary, resulting in algal blooms and the deaths of wildlife. But Brevard Zoo recognized the importance of using the oysterâs natural ability to filter water as a way to improve the water quality of the Indian River Lagoon.\r\n\r\nThe Eastern oyster, Crassotrea virginica, was once found in abundance along the Indian River Lagoon but has now disappeared from many portions of the waterway. The native oyster population was decimated by a combination of factors; including coastal construction, overharvesting, pollution, disease and boat wakes. Oysters are an essential part of the Indian River lagoon ecosystem for many reasons. They are a keystone species that numerous other species depend on for food and habitat. Oysters are also gregarious, which means that individuals clump together, creating natural reefs that help prevent shoreline erosion.\r\n\r\n<img class="alignnone  wp-image-684" alt="why3" src="http://brevardoystergardens.org/wp-content/uploads/2014/03/why31.jpg" width="803" height="504" />\r\n\r\nBut most importantly, oysters are filter feeders, which means that they consume organic material present in the waters of the lagoon, thereby cleaning the water. In fact, one average adult oyster can filter up to 50 gallons of water per day. Imagine how many gallons of filtered water this would add up to over an oysterâs 20 year life span!Â Their filtering abilities help to reduce the amount of algae and muck floating in the river, and the resulting improved water clarity and light penetration is especially important for sea grass, another keystone species in the Indian River Lagoon.\r\n\r\nSo, in 2005, Brevard Zoo partnered with the University of Central Florida to restore oyster reefs throughout the Mosquito Lagoon portion of the Indian River Lagoon in Volusia County.Â The reefs are created using a quilt-like pattern of "oyster mats", which was developed by UCF''s Dr. Linda Walters. The oyster mats provide new habitat for free-swimming oyster larvae, and since 2005, more than 42,000 mats have been made and deployed, establishing 68 new oyster reefs, thanks to the help of more than 40,000 volunteers.\r\n\r\n<img class="alignnone  wp-image-712" alt="Home4" src="http://brevardoystergardens.org/wp-content/uploads/2014/04/Home4.jpg" width="1430" height="1073" />\r\n\r\nMore recently, Brevard Zoo has also Â partnered with Brevard County to launch the Oyster Gardening Project. This is a community-based project that relies on the efforts of citizen scientists to grow oysters and collect data on oyster survivability in the Indian River Lagoon in order to facilitate the construction of oyster restoration reefs in Brevard County.\r\n\r\nResidents living along the lagoon volunteer to create oyster habitats and deploy them off of their docks. The habitats are then populated with living oyster spats (attached oyster larvae) and are monitored weekly for signs of recruitment and survivability. This data is used to determine locations for large-scale oyster reef restoration projects, similar to the work currently being done in Mosquito Lagoon, and the oysters grown through the program are used to populate the reefs. In the fall of 2014, construction began on the very first Brevard County oyster reefs.\r\n\r\n<b>For more information about the issues affecting the Indian River Lagoon, please refer to the following news articles:</b>\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li><a href="http://www.nytimes.com/2013/08/08/us/deaths-of-manatees-dolphins-and-pelicans-point-to-estuary-at-risk.html?_r=0" target="_blank">âDeaths of Manatees, Dolphins and Pelicans Point to Estuary at Riskâ</a><a href="http://www.nytimes.com/2013/08/08/us/deaths-of-manatees-dolphins-and-pelicans-point-to-estuary-at-risk.html?_r=0">-Â </a>New York Times</li>\r\n	<li><a href="http://www.floridatoday.com/article/20130918/NEWS01/309180014/Algae-related-fish-kills-plague-Indian-River-Lagoon" target="_blank">âAlgae-related fish kills plague Indian River Lagoonâ</a>- Florida Today</li>\r\n	<li>Letter from Keith Winsten, Executive Director of Brevard ZooÂ <a href="http://www.floridatoday.com/article/20130903/NEWS01/309030001/Keith-Winsten-Lagoon-needs-our-help-now-survive" target="_blank">âLagoon needs our help now to surviveâ</a>Â - Florida Today</li>\r\n	<li><a href="http://articles.orlandosentinel.com/2014-02-01/news/os-manatee-deaths-indian-river-20140201_1_indian-river-lagoon-katie-tripp-dead-manatees" target="_blank">âManatee deaths unsolved amid effort to reverse Indian River collapseâ</a>Â - Orlando Sentinel</li>\r\n	<li><a href="http://www.floridatoday.com/story/news/local/environment/lagoon/2014/05/03/indian-river-lagoon-went-wrong/8672245/?sf25781894=%5B%271%27%5D" target="_blank">âIndian River Lagoon: What went wrong?â</a>âFlorida Today</li>\r\n	<li><a href="http://creative.news-journalonline.com/troubledwater/" target="_blank">âTroubled Water: The Indian River Lagoon in Perilâ</a>-Daytona Beach News-Journal</li>\r\n	<li><a href="http://www.floridatoday.com/story/news/local/environment/2014/08/06/cities-ponder-new-ponds-higher-fees-to-meet-lagoon-pollution-limits/13670487/" target="_blank">"Cleaning Indian River Lagoon will cost $1.4 billion"</a> âFlorida Today</li>\r\n	<li><a href="http://www.floridatoday.com/article/20130912/NEWS01/309120023/Oysters-key-plan-might-save-Indian-River-Lagoon">"Oyster are Key to a Plan That Might Save Indian River Lagoon"</a> âFlorida Today</li>\r\n	<li>"<a href="http://www.clickorlando.com/news/community-works-to-restore-oyster-beds-in-brevard-county/21888830">Community Works to Restore Oyster Beds</a>" âWKMG Local 6</li>\r\n	<li><a href="http://www.wesh.com/indian-river-lagoon-oyster-experiment-shows-promise/25521854#!FmnHB" target="_blank">âIndian River Lagoon Oyster Experiment Shows Promiseâ</a>â Wesh Orlando</li>\r\n	<li>"<a href="http://www.floridatoday.com/story/news/local/environment/2014/07/30/brevard-zoo-to-double-oyster-efforts/13358867/?from=global&amp;sessionKey=&amp;autologin=" target="_blank">Brevard Zoo to Double Oyster Efforts</a>"â Florida Today</li>\r\n	<li><a href="http://www.wesh.com/news/could-backyard-oyster-growing-help-restore-the-troubled-irl/29647236" target="_blank">"Could Backyard Oyster Growing Restore the Troubled IRL?"</a> âWesh 2 News</li>\r\n	<li>"<a href="http://today.ucf.edu/oysters-rescue-natural-way-clean-indian-river-lagoon/" target="_blank">Oysters To The Rescue? A Natural Way To Clean Up The Indian River Lagoon</a>." âUCF Today</li>\r\n</ul>', 'Home', '', 'inherit', 'closed', 'open', '', '587-revision-v1', '', '', '2014-11-20 19:29:49', '2014-11-20 19:29:49', '', 587, 'http://brevardoystergardens.org/587-revision-v1/', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
