(1188, 5, '2014-11-18 21:11:56', '2014-11-18 21:11:56', '<em>The Indian River Lagoon watershed can be cleaned up if we take the following steps...</em>\r\n\r\n<img class="alignnone  wp-image-28" alt="" src="http://brevardoystergardens.org/wp-content/uploads/2014/03/Watershed1.jpg" width="1177" height="802" />\r\n\r\n<b>Reduce: </b>Stormwater runoff can be detrimental to the lagoon by causing changes in nutrient and salinity levels as well as introducing pollutants, so the Brevard County Natural Resources Management Department is working on reducing the amount of stormwater discharge that enters the Indian River Lagoon. The <a href="http://www.brevardcounty.us/NaturalResources/Watershed/Home" target="_blank">Brevard County Stormwater Program</a> was created by the Board of County Commissioners in 1990, and since the early â90s, the county has invested $34 million dollars in stormwater treatment projects to either hold or purify water before it enters the lagoon. Over 450 projects have been completed, resulting in the treatment of 21,000 acres worth of stormwater, and the Brevard County Natural Resources Management Department continues to work on additional projects, the details of which can be found on their <a href="http://www.brevardcounty.us/NaturalResources/Home" target="_blank">homepage</a>.\r\n\r\nThe St. Johns River Water Management District is also responsible for managing groundwater and surface water resources in 18 counties, including Brevard County. They work directly on water supply to these counties, as well as with flood protection, water quality issues, and management of natural systems. Their <a href="http://floridaswater.com/" target="_blank">website</a> and special <a href="http://www.sjrwmd.com/irlupdate/" target="_blank">Indian River Lagoon Update</a> are excellent resources for up-to-date information on the Indian River Lagoon, including current issues and the steps being taken to find solutions. Also be sure to check out their extensive current and archivalÂ <a href="http://webapub.sjrwmd.com/agws10/hdswq/" target="_blank"><span style="text-decoration: underline;">water quality data</span></a>Â and visitÂ <a href="http://www.itsyourlagoon.com" target="_blank"><span style="text-decoration: underline;">Itâs Your Lagoon</span></a>Â for more current news and information concerning Indian River Lagoon water management initiatives.\r\n\r\n<img class="alignnone  wp-image-857" alt="" src="http://brevardoystergardens.org/wp-content/uploads/2014/07/Screen-Shot-2014-07-09-at-3.04.39-PM.png" width="640" height="547" />\r\n\r\n<b>Remove: </b>Within the Indian River Lagoon, tremendous layers of detrimental muck fill the estuary floor. This muck contains contaminants that have entered the lagoon from stormwater discharge and runoff from residential properties and other point sources. These contaminants remain in the muck, creating a layer of uninhabitable soil. This layer needs to be surgically removed from the Indian River Lagoon in order to restore essential habitat for keystone species such as seagrass. So Brevard County is working diligently to acquire the necessary funding to remove this detrimental muck from our lagoon. A great read on the topic is <a href="http://www.floridatoday.com/article/20140127/ENVIRONMENT/301270032/Muck-arch-enemy-lurks-deep-Indian-River-Lagoon" target="_blank">âMuck: The arch-enemy lurks deep in Indian River Lagoonâ</a>, written by Florida Today.<b></b>\r\n\r\n<img class="alignnone  wp-image-74" alt="Deployment2" src="http://brevardoystergardens.org/wp-content/uploads/2014/03/Deployment21.png" width="650" height="488" />\r\n\r\n<b>Research and Restore: </b>This is where the Brevard Oyster Restoration project comes in. The Brevard Zooâs Brevard Oyster Restoration project currently has two programs dedicated to restoring the Indian River Lagoon by bolstering the areaâs native oyster population. The Oyster Mats program focuses solely on physically rebuilding oyster reefs in the Mosquito Lagoon portion of the Indian River Lagoon, while the Oyster Gardening program recruits residents along the Indian River Lagoon to Â both grow oysters and provide data about the survivability and recruitment of oysters in Brevard County to help determine the sites for local reef rebuilding projects. Research is the foundation for any successful restoration project, so we are working very closely with academia on both the Oyster Mats and Oyster Gardening projects in order to ensure our efforts are as successful as they can be.<b></b>\r\n\r\nDr. Linda Walters of the<a href="http://www.ucf.edu/" target="_blank">Â University of Central Florida</a>Â is the science behind the Oyster Mats technique being used in Mosquito Lagoon. She and her team of researchers continue to monitor the oyster reefs each year, collecting data concerning the survivability, growth, Â and recruitment and Â of Â oysters in Mosquito Lagoon, as well as their affects on other keystone species, like seagrass. For the Oyster Gardening project, Â all of the data our citizen scientists collect throughout the project is entered into a database where it is analyzed in order to determine oyster reef restoration sites. Size and weight data are also collected on oysters returned at the conclusion of the gardening program, and once they are placed on the new reefs, they are monitored for signs of health, growth and recruitment.', 'Saving The Lagoon', '', 'inherit', 'closed', 'open', '', '851-revision-v1', '', '', '2014-11-18 21:11:56', '2014-11-18 21:11:56', '', 851, 'http://brevardoystergardens.org/851-revision-v1/', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
