(682, 3, '2014-04-11 00:21:43', '2014-04-11 00:21:43', '<a href="http://brevardoystergardens.org/wp-content/uploads/2014/03/why11.png"><img class="alignnone size-full wp-image-681" alt="why1" src="http://brevardoystergardens.org/wp-content/uploads/2014/03/why11.png" width="512" height="270" /></a>\n\nDid you know oysters can actually swim for the first two weeks of their lives? Adult oysters release their gametes into the water, where they join and create a fertilized egg that will become a free-swimming larvae. For the next two weeks, this oyster larvae is traveling through the Indian River Lagoon looking for a place to live. This is a very important decision because after these two weeks, the oysters are stationary and they will stay in the same location for the rest of their lives.\n\n<a href="http://darrengriffith.net/wp/wp-content/uploads/2014/03/why2.jpg"><img class="alignnone size-medium wp-image-142" alt="why2" src="http://darrengriffith.net/wp/wp-content/uploads/2014/03/why2-300x225.jpg" width="300" height="225" /></a>\n\n&nbsp;\n\n<a href="http://darrengriffith.net/wp/wp-content/uploads/2014/03/why3.jpg"><img class="alignnone size-medium wp-image-143" alt="why3" src="http://darrengriffith.net/wp/wp-content/uploads/2014/03/why3-300x188.jpg" width="300" height="188" /></a>\n\nOysters are gregarious species, meaning they prefer to live among other oysters. As this free-swimming larvae is floating through the lagoon, sometimes for miles, they are looking for other oysters to settle with. They also require a hard substrate to attach to, where they can grow and build their shell composed of calcium. The average life span of the Eastern Oyster, <i>Crassostrea virginica</i>, is approximately 20 years.', 'Why Oysters?', '', 'inherit', 'open', 'open', '', '140-autosave-v1', '', '', '2014-04-11 00:21:43', '2014-04-11 00:21:43', '', 140, 'http://brevardoystergardens.org/?p=682', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
