(691, 3, '2014-04-11 00:26:25', '2014-04-11 00:26:25', '', '', 'Disease: Just like we get colds and flus, oysters suffer from two diseases that are specific to them: Dermo and MSX. These particular diseases can spread and cause the oyster population to decline as a result.', 'inherit', 'open', 'open', '', 'threats6', '', '', '2014-04-11 00:26:25', '2014-04-11 00:26:25', '', 140, 'http://brevardoystergardens.org/wp-content/uploads/2014/03/threats61.jpg', 0, 'attachment', 'image/jpeg', 0),
(692, 3, '2014-04-11 00:26:49', '2014-04-11 00:26:49', '', '', 'BOAT WAKES: Large waves produced by a moving vessel on the Indian River Lagoon can dislodge oysters from the reef. Once the oysters are off the reef, they canât just walk right back on to it and live happily ever after. Dislodged oysters will roll in the waves, ultimately forming piles in the shallow water, where they will dry out and die. The resulting large piles of oyster shells are referred to as dead margins.', 'inherit', 'open', 'open', '', 'threats7', '', '', '2014-04-11 00:26:49', '2014-04-11 00:26:49', '', 140, 'http://brevardoystergardens.org/wp-content/uploads/2014/03/threats71.jpg', 0, 'attachment', 'image/jpeg', 0),
