(937, 5, '2014-07-10 14:50:07', '2014-07-10 14:50:07', '<a href="http://brevardoystergardens.org/wp-content/uploads/2014/04/Screen-Shot-2014-07-09-at-4.31.19-PM.png"><img class="alignnone size-full wp-image-884" alt="" src="http://brevardoystergardens.org/wp-content/uploads/2014/04/Screen-Shot-2014-07-09-at-4.31.19-PM.png" width="940" height="623" /></a>\r\n\r\nSpanning 156 miles and five Florida counties, the Indian River Lagoon is one of the most biologically diverse estuaries in the country, providing a home for more than 4,000 species of plants and animals. The vast majority of this waterway, which includes the Mosquito Lagoon area and both the Banana and Indian rivers, is located here in Brevard County, providing our community with a one-of-a-kind ecological and recreational treasure that also has an estimated economic value of $3.7 billon per year.\r\n\r\nHowever, in recent years, the lagoon has seen increasing threats to its water quality and biological diversity. Continuous inputs of pollution have overloaded the estuary, resulting in algal blooms and the deaths of wildlife. But Brevard Zoo recognized the importance of using the oysterâs natural ability to filter water as a way to improve the water quality of the Indian River Lagoon.\r\n\r\n<a href="http://brevardoystergardens.org/wp-content/uploads/2014/03/why31.jpg"><img class="alignnone size-full wp-image-684" alt="why3" src="http://brevardoystergardens.org/wp-content/uploads/2014/03/why31.jpg" width="803" height="504" /></a>\r\n\r\nThe Eastern oyster, <i>Crassotrea virginica,</i> was once found in abundance along the Indian River Lagoon but has now disappeared from many portions of the waterway. The native oyster population was decimated by a combination of factors; including habitat loss, overharvesting, pollution, reduced water quality, disease and boat wakes. Oysters are an essential part of the Indian River lagoon ecosystem for many reasons. They are a keystone species that numerous other species depend on for food and protection. Oysters are also gregarious, which means that individuals clump together, creating natural reefs that help prevent erosion.\r\n\r\nBut most importantly, oysters are filter feeders, which means that they consume organic material present in the waters of the lagoon, thereby cleaning the water. In fact, one average adult oyster can filter up to 50 gallons of water per day. Imagine how many gallons of filtered water this would add up to over an oysterâs 20 year life span!Â Their filtering abilities help to reduce the amount of algae and muck floating in the river, and the resulting improved water clarity and light penetration is especially important for sea grass, another keystone species in the Indian River Lagoon.\r\n\r\n<a href="http://brevardoystergardens.org/wp-content/uploads/2014/04/Home4.jpg"><img class="alignnone size-full wp-image-712" alt="Home4" src="http://brevardoystergardens.org/wp-content/uploads/2014/04/Home4.jpg" width="1430" height="1073" /></a>\r\n\r\nSo, in 2005, Brevard Zoo partnered with the University of Central Florida to restore oyster reefs in the Mosquito Lagoon portion of the Indian River Lagoon.Â The reefs are created using a quilt-like pattern of oyster mats, which was developed by Dr. Linda Walters. Since that time, over 36,000 mats have been made and deployed, establishing 63 new oyster reefs, thanks to the help of over 36,000 volunteers.\r\n\r\nBrevard Zoo has also recently partnered with Brevard County to launch the Oyster Gardening Project. This is a community-based project that relies on the efforts of citizen scientists to collect data on oyster survivability in the Indian River Lagoon. Residents living along the lagoon volunteer to create oyster habitats and deploy them off of their docks. The habitats are then populated with living oyster spats (attached oyster larvae) and are monitored weekly for signs of recruitment and survivability. This data will be used to determine locations for future large-scale oyster reef restoration projects similar to the work currently being done in Mosquito Lagoon.\r\n\r\n<b>For more information about the issues affecting the Indian River Lagoon, please refer to the following articles:</b>\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li><a href="http://www.nytimes.com/2013/08/08/us/deaths-of-manatees-dolphins-and-pelicans-point-to-estuary-at-risk.html?_r=0" target="_blank">âDeaths of Manatees, Dolphins and Pelicans Point to Estuary at Riskâ</a><a href="http://www.nytimes.com/2013/08/08/us/deaths-of-manatees-dolphins-and-pelicans-point-to-estuary-at-risk.html?_r=0">-Â </a>New York Times</li>\r\n	<li><a href="http://www.floridatoday.com/article/20130918/NEWS01/309180014/Algae-related-fish-kills-plague-Indian-River-Lagoon" target="_blank">âAlgae-related fish kills plague Indian River Lagoonâ</a>- Florida Today</li>\r\n	<li>Letter from Keith Winsten, Executive Director of Brevard ZooÂ <a href="http://www.floridatoday.com/article/20130903/NEWS01/309030001/Keith-Winsten-Lagoon-needs-our-help-now-survive" target="_blank">âLagoon needs our help now to surviveâ</a>Â - Florida Today</li>\r\n	<li><a href="http://articles.orlandosentinel.com/2014-02-01/news/os-manatee-deaths-indian-river-20140201_1_indian-river-lagoon-katie-tripp-dead-manatees" target="_blank">âManatee deaths unsolved amid effort to reverse Indian River collapseâ</a>Â - Orlando Sentinel</li>\r\n	<li><a href="http://www.floridatoday.com/article/20131126/NEWS01/311260012/Living-dock-might-help-heal-lagoon" target="_blank">âGirl Scoutsâ Living Dock Might Help Heal Indian River Lagoonâ</a>âFlorida Today</li>\r\n	<li><a href="http://www.wesh.com/indian-river-lagoon-oyster-experiment-shows-promise/25521854#!FmnHB" target="_blank">âIndian River Lagoon Oyster Experiment Shows Promiseâ</a>â Wesh Orlando</li>\r\n	<li><a href="http://www.floridatoday.com/story/news/local/environment/lagoon/2014/05/03/indian-river-lagoon-went-wrong/8672245/?sf25781894=%5B%271%27%5D" target="_blank">âIndian River Lagoon: What went wrong?â</a>âFlorida Today</li>\r\n	<li><a href="http://creative.news-journalonline.com/troubledwater/" target="_blank">âTroubled Water: The Indian River Lagoon in Perilâ</a>-Daytona Beach News-Journal</li>\r\n</ul>', 'Home', '', 'inherit', 'closed', 'open', '', '587-revision-v1', '', '', '2014-07-10 14:50:07', '2014-07-10 14:50:07', '', 587, 'http://brevardoystergardens.org/?p=937', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
(938, 5, '2014-07-10 14:53:02', '2014-07-10 14:53:02', '<a href="http://brevardoystergardens.org/wp-content/uploads/2014/03/Watershed1.jpg"><img class="alignnone size-full wp-image-28" alt="" src="http://brevardoystergardens.org/wp-content/uploads/2014/03/Watershed1.jpg" width="1177" height="802" /></a>\r\n\r\n<b>Reduce: </b>Stormwater runoff can be detrimental to the lagoon by causing changes in nutrient and salinity levels as well as introducing pollutants, so the Brevard County Natural Resources Management Department is working on reducing the amount of stormwater discharge that enters the Indian River Lagoon. The <a href="http://www.brevardcounty.us/NaturalResources/Watershed/Home" target="_blank">Brevard County Stormwater Program</a> was created by the Board of County Commissioners in 1990, and since the early â90s, the county has invested $34 million dollars in stormwater treatment projects to either hold or purify water before it enters the lagoon. Over 450 projects have been completed, resulting in the treatment of 21,000 acres worth of stormwater, and the Brevard County Natural Resources Management Department continues to work on additional projects, the details of which can be found on their <a href="http://www.brevardcounty.us/NaturalResources/Home" target="_blank">homepage</a>.\r\n\r\nThe St. Johns River Water Management District is also responsible for managing groundwater and surface water resources in 18 counties, including Brevard County. They work directly on water supply to these counties, as well as with flood protection, water quality issues, and management of natural systems. Their <a href="http://floridaswater.com/" target="_blank">website</a> and special <a href="http://www.sjrwmd.com/irlupdate/" target="_blank">Indian River Lagoon Update</a> are excellent resources for up-to-date information on the Indian River Lagoon, including current issues and the steps being taken to find solutions. Also be sure to check out their extensive current and archivalÂ <a href="http://webapub.sjrwmd.com/agws10/hdswq/" target="_blank"><span style="text-decoration: underline;">water quality data</span></a>Â and visitÂ <a href="http://www.itsyourlagoon.com" target="_blank"><span style="text-decoration: underline;">Itâs Your Lagoon</span></a>Â for more current news and information concerning Indian River Lagoon water management initiatives.\r\n\r\n<a href="http://brevardoystergardens.org/wp-content/uploads/2014/07/Screen-Shot-2014-07-09-at-3.04.39-PM.png"><img class="alignnone size-full wp-image-857" alt="" src="http://brevardoystergardens.org/wp-content/uploads/2014/07/Screen-Shot-2014-07-09-at-3.04.39-PM.png" width="640" height="547" /></a>\r\n\r\n<b>Remove: </b>Within the Indian River Lagoon, tremendous layers of detrimental muck fill the estuary floor. This muck contains contaminants that have entered the lagoon from stormwater discharge and runoff from residential properties and other point sources. These contaminants remain in the muck, creating a layer of uninhabitable soil. This layer needs to be surgically removed from the Indian River Lagoon in order to restore essential habitat for keystone species such as seagrass. So Brevard County is working diligently to acquire the necessary funding to remove this detrimental muck from our lagoon. A great read on the topic is <a href="http://www.floridatoday.com/article/20140127/ENVIRONMENT/301270032/Muck-arch-enemy-lurks-deep-Indian-River-Lagoon" target="_blank">âMuck: The arch-enemy lurks deep in Indian River Lagoonâ</a>, written by Florida Today.<b></b>\r\n\r\n<a href="http://brevardoystergardens.org/wp-content/uploads/2014/03/Deployment21.png"><img class="alignnone size-full wp-image-74" alt="Deployment2" src="http://brevardoystergardens.org/wp-content/uploads/2014/03/Deployment21.png" width="650" height="488" /></a>\r\n\r\n<b>Research and Restore: </b>This is where the Brevard Oyster Restoration project comes in. The Brevard Zooâs Brevard Oyster Restoration project currently has two programs dedicated to restoring the Indian River Lagoon by bolstering the areaâs native oyster population. The Oyster Mats program focuses on physically rebuilding oyster reefs in the Mosquito Lagoon portion of the Indian River Lagoon, while the Oyster Gardening program is recruiting residents along the Indian River Lagoon to help provide us with data about the survivability and recruitment of oysters in Brevard County in order to determine sites for future reef rebuilding projects. Research is the foundation for any successful restoration project, so we are working very closely with academia on both the Oyster Mats and Oyster Gardening project in order to ensure our efforts are as successful as they can be.<b></b>\r\n\r\nDr. Linda Walters of the<a href="http://www.ucf.edu/" target="_blank">Â University of Central Florida</a>Â is the science behind the Oyster Mats technique being used in Mosquito Lagoon. She and her team of researchers continue to monitor the oyster reefs each year, collecting data concerning the survivability, growth, recruitment and predation of the oysters in Mosquito Lagoon. For the Oyster Gardening project, Â all of the data our citizen scientists collect throughout the project will be entered into a database where it can then be analyzed for further interpretation.', 'Steps To Saving The Lagoon', '', 'inherit', 'closed', 'open', '', '851-revision-v1', '', '', '2014-07-10 14:53:02', '2014-07-10 14:53:02', '', 851, 'http://brevardoystergardens.org/?p=938', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
(939, 5, '2014-07-10 14:59:21', '2014-07-10 14:59:21', '<a href="http://brevardoystergardens.org/wp-content/uploads/2014/04/Home7.jpg"><img class="alignnone size-full wp-image-716" alt="Home7" src="http://brevardoystergardens.org/wp-content/uploads/2014/04/Home7.jpg" width="974" height="773" /></a>\r\n\r\nTheÂ Brevard Oyster Gardening project, launched by Brevard Zoo in partnership with the Brevard County Natural Resources Management Office, is encouraging the community to get involved with the process of repairing damages to the lagoon. Inspired by the oyster reef restoration work that Brevard Zoo has been doing with UCF in Mosquito Lagoon, the Oyster Gardening Project seeks to expand reef restoration intoÂ Brevard Countyâs portion of theÂ Indian River Lagoon by first identifying areas with high rates of oyster survivability and recruitment that are good candidate locations for a future reef restoration project.\r\n\r\nIn order to collect the necessary data, the Brevard County Commissioners funded the project with $150,000 to supply a small staff and provide the necessary equipment to train volunteers in Brevard County to become âoyster gardeners.â The project relies almost entirely on <a href="http://mapalist.com/Public/pm.aspx?mapid=435233" target="_blank">these volunteers</a> living along the shores of the Indian River Lagoon who agree to hang oyster habitats from their docks and then monitor those habitats to collect data on the growth, survivability, and recruitment of oysters in their area, all of which gets entered into a database on a weekly basis for a period of about six to seven months.\r\n\r\n<a href="http://brevardoystergardens.org/wp-content/uploads/2014/03/Oysters_Kiwanis-Park-361.jpg"><img class="alignnone size-full wp-image-596" alt="Oysters_Kiwanis Park 36" src="http://brevardoystergardens.org/wp-content/uploads/2014/03/Oysters_Kiwanis-Park-361.jpg" width="3312" height="2704" /></a>\r\n\r\nOyster gardeners first attend a special workshop where they learn all the details of the program and build their own oyster habitats. Later, they receive oyster shells covered with live spat (juvenile oysters), which they place into their habitats and then deploy from their docks, beginning the data collection process. To ensure the greatest probability of success, the oyster spat used in the Oyster Gardening project are spawned from a local brood stock near Sebastian, FL. Their spawning takes place at the Florida Oceanographic Society, in a hatchery dedicated to the reproduction of the Eastern Oyster. Using a local population of oysters from Brevard County to parent these oyster spat will keep future generations of oysters in potential restored populations genetically similar to those that once made up the areaâs original population.\r\n\r\n[gallery ids="658,654,656"]', 'Oyster Gardening Program', '', 'inherit', 'closed', 'open', '', '899-revision-v1', '', '', '2014-07-10 14:59:21', '2014-07-10 14:59:21', '', 899, 'http://brevardoystergardens.org/?p=939', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
(942, 5, '2014-07-10 15:05:47', '2014-07-10 15:05:47', '<strong>REFERENCE DOCUMENTS</strong>\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li><a href="http://brevardoystergardens.org/wp-content/uploads/2014/06/oystergardeningPPT_2014.pdf" target="_blank">Oyster Gardening Presentation</a></li>\r\n	<li><a href="http://brevardoystergardens.org/wp-content/uploads/2014/03/Brevard-Oyster-Gardening-Manual-Version-11.pdf" target="_blank">Brevard Oyster Gardening Manual</a></li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<strong>OYSTER SPAT IDENTIFICATION GUIDES</strong>\r\n\r\nOyster spat 3 weeks post-distribution:\r\n\r\n[gallery ids="740,739,737"]\r\n\r\nOyster spat 5 weeks post-distribution:\r\n\r\n[gallery ids="743,742"]\r\n\r\nOyster spat under fouling:\r\n\r\n[gallery columns="4" ids="843,844,845,849"]\r\n\r\n<strong>OYSTER COHABITANTS IDENTIFICATION GUIDES</strong>\r\n\r\nOyster friends:\r\n\r\n[gallery ids="773,775,727,817,819,820"]\r\n\r\nOyster foes:\r\n\r\n[gallery ids="728,726,725,722,721,768,772,771,770"]\r\n\r\nFound something in your habitat that you don''t see here? Look it up in the Smithsonian Marine Station''sÂ <a href="http://www.sms.si.edu/irlspec/SpeciesImageGallery.htm" target="_blank">Indian River Lagoon Species Database</a>.', 'Oyster Gardening Resources', '', 'inherit', 'closed', 'open', '', '906-revision-v1', '', '', '2014-07-10 15:05:47', '2014-07-10 15:05:47', '', 906, 'http://brevardoystergardens.org/?p=942', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
(947, 5, '2014-07-10 15:11:24', '2014-07-10 15:11:24', '&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<a style="line-height: 1.5;" href="http://brevardoystergardens.org/wp-content/uploads/2014/03/bz-logo.jpeg"><img class="alignnone size-full wp-image-916" alt="bz logo" src="http://brevardoystergardens.org/wp-content/uploads/2014/03/bz-logo.jpeg" width="358" height="141" /></a>\r\n\r\n<a href="http://www.brevardzoo.org/" target="_blank">Brevard Zoo</a>Â is a small zoo that does big things. We focus providing top quality care for our animals, offering unique opportunities for guests to experience nature both on- and off-site, and actively participating with Brevard County Public Schools to develop education programs that serve diverse audiences with authentic learning. Our mission is âWildlife Conservation through Education and Participation,â and the Brevard Oyster Restoration project team at Brevard Zoo actively follows this mission through the Oyster Mats and Oyster Gardening programs by working directly with the community to actively restore the Indian River Lagoon. Brevard Zoo houses all of the staff and supplies for each project, including a giant pile of oyster shells collected from local restaurants.<b>Â </b>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<a href="http://brevardoystergardens.org/wp-content/uploads/2014/03/Screen-Shot-2014-07-10-at-10.23.34-AM.png"><img class="alignnone  wp-image-923" alt="" src="http://brevardoystergardens.org/wp-content/uploads/2014/03/Screen-Shot-2014-07-10-at-10.23.34-AM.png" width="334" height="170" /></a>\r\n\r\nTheÂ <a href="http://www.brevardcounty.us/NaturalResources" target="_blank">Brevard County Natural Resources Management Department</a>, along with the County Commissioners, provided $150,000 to fund the Oyster Gardening project. That money has been used to purchase supplies for hundreds of oyster gardeners in Brevard County and hire a small staff to lead the project. The county is actively involved in educating the public about the issues facing the Indian River Lagoon and the steps being taken within our community to provide solutions.\r\n\r\n<b>Â </b>\r\n\r\n<a href="http://brevardoystergardens.org/wp-content/uploads/2014/03/DUCF36__55990.1360004520.1280.1280.jpg"><img class="alignnone  wp-image-918" alt="" src="http://brevardoystergardens.org/wp-content/uploads/2014/03/DUCF36__55990.1360004520.1280.1280.jpg" width="361" height="361" /></a>\r\n\r\nUse of Oyster Mats for oyster reef restoration was pioneered by <a href="http://biology.cos.ucf.edu/faculty/linda-walters/" target="_blank">Dr. Linda Walters</a>, of the <a href="http://www.ucf.edu/" target="_blank">University of Central Florida</a>, and has proven to be a successful scientific-based restoration technique.Â Together, UCF and Brevard Zoo deploy these mats into Mosquito Lagoon at designated restoration sites and continue to monitor their progress through research and data collection. In addition to oyster mat restoration, University of Central Florida is leading living shoreline stabilization efforts in Canaveral National Seashore and aiming to <a href="http://today.ucf.edu/ucf-app-aims-prevent-boat-mishaps-protect-mosquito-lagoon/" target="_blank">reduce boating collisions</a> with oyster reefs.\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<a href="http://brevardoystergardens.org/wp-content/uploads/2014/03/Eastern_Florida_State_College_Logo.png"><img class="alignnone size-full wp-image-919" alt="" src="http://brevardoystergardens.org/wp-content/uploads/2014/03/Eastern_Florida_State_College_Logo.png" width="357" height="200" /></a>\r\n\r\nThe <a href="http://www.easternflorida.edu/" target="_blank">Eastern Florida State College</a> Environmental Club of the Melbourne Campus seeks to promote environmental stewardship through the service of its members, educate the public on the importance of maintaining a healthy ecosystem through community outreach, and support the Eastern Florida State College Melbourne Campus in its efforts to pursue and maintain a sustainable environment. The club is fulfilling this mission statement through the countless hours of preparation work its members do for oyster gardening workshops, including cutting wire to create oyster habitats.\r\n\r\n<a href="http://brevardoystergardens.org/wp-content/uploads/2014/03/UF_Logo.jpg"><img class="alignnone size-full wp-image-920" alt="" src="http://brevardoystergardens.org/wp-content/uploads/2014/03/UF_Logo.jpg" width="1194" height="365" /></a>\r\nThe <a href="http://brevard.ifas.ufl.edu" target="_blank">University Of Florida IFAS</a> Extension Brevard County is partnering with Brevard County and Brevard Zoo to teach waterfront property owners about how to get involved with the Oyster Gardening program. Meanwhile, the <a href="http://www.flseagrant.org/" target="_blank">Florida Sea Grant</a> Extension agent for Brevard County provides educational opportunities and university research-based information on a variety of topics and issues to the citizens of Brevard County.\r\n\r\n<a href="http://brevardoystergardens.org/wp-content/uploads/2014/03/Screen-Shot-2014-07-10-at-10.20.06-AM.png"><img class="alignnone size-full wp-image-921" alt="" src="http://brevardoystergardens.org/wp-content/uploads/2014/03/Screen-Shot-2014-07-10-at-10.20.06-AM.png" width="563" height="163" /></a>\r\n\r\n<a href="http://www.modusoperandi.com/" target="_blank">Modus Operandi</a>Â is high-tech software company specializing in delivering technology that helps organizations discover the hidden patterns locked in their data. Modus Operandi employees were involved with the initial development of this website.', 'Our Partners', '', 'inherit', 'closed', 'open', '', '188-revision-v1', '', '', '2014-07-10 15:11:24', '2014-07-10 15:11:24', '', 188, 'http://brevardoystergardens.org/?p=947', 0, 'revision', '', 0);
