evardcounty.us/NaturalResources/Watershed/PollutionPrevention">\r\n</a></li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<b>Helpful Organizations In Our Area:</b>\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li><a href="http://www.bluelifefl.org/" target="_blank">Blue Life Florida</a> is a cooperative partnership among non-profit organizations, local governments, businesses, educational institutions and residents determined to reduce the pollutant load to our nationally acclaimed bodies of water, including the Indian River Lagoon, St. Johns River, and the many tributaries that flow into them.</li>\r\n	<li><a href="http://brevard.ifas.ufl.edu/horticulture/" target="_blank">My Brevard Yard Program</a> teaches you<b> </b>how to grow a healthy landscape, protect the environment, and save money, all at the same time!</li>\r\n	<li>The <a href="http://www.sms.si.edu/SMEE/index.htm" target="_blank">Smithsonian Marine Ecosystems Exhibit</a> is a great place to visit for some educational fun.</li>\r\n	<li>The <a href="http://research.fit.edu/irlri/index.php" target="_blank">Florida Tech Indian River Lagoon Research Institute</a> has lots of great volunteer and event opportunities, and be sure to sign up for a <a href="http://camps.fit.edu/dmes/" target="_blank">Florida Tech Marine &amp; Environmental Science Summer Camp</a>, available for ages 10 and up.</li>\r\n	<li>The <a href="http://spoilislandproject.org/" target="_blank">Florida DEP Indian River Lagoon Spoil Island Project</a> has visitor information and volunteer opportunities.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<b>National Oyster Restoration Initiatives:</b>\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>The Brevard Oyster Gardening Project was modeled after many established oyster gardening projects, such as the current project in <a href="http://www.cbf.org/how-we-save-the-bay/programs-initiatives/maryland/oyster-restoration/oyster-gardening-program" target="_blank">Chesapeake Bay</a>. Give this <a href="http://blog.nature.org/science/2013/11/18/coastal-protection-and-clean-water-recognizing-the-benefits-of-oyster-reefs/?utm_source=feedburner&amp;utm_medium=email&amp;utm_campaign=Feed%3A+CoolGreenScience+%28Cool+Green+Science%29" target="_blank">Nature Conservancy article</a> a read for more information on projects across the nation.</li>\r\n</ul>', 'Additional Resources', '', 'inherit', 'closed', 'open', '', '929-revision-v1', '', '', '2014-08-25 19:15:59', '2014-08-25 19:15:59', '', 929, 'http://brevardoystergardens.org/929-revision-v1/', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
(945, 5, '2014-07-10 15:10:02', '2014-07-10 15:10:02', '<a href="http://brevardoystergardens.org/wp-content/uploads/2014/03/OysterMat11.png"><img class="alignnone size-full wp-image-53" alt="OysterMat1" src="http://brevardoystergardens.org/wp-content/uploads/2014/03/OysterMat11.png" width="1018" height="652" /></a>\r\n\r\n<b>Other Ways To Help Protect Our Lagoon</b>\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>Reduce lawn fertilizer, pesticides, and pet waste, and keep waste out of storm drains. Excessive nutrient runoff into the lagoon from fertilizers and pesticides contributes to algal blooms, and a large amount of the fecal coliform bacteria present in storm water runoff originates from pet waste. Meanwhile, chemicals and trash items that are dumped into storm drains throughout the county all end up in the lagoon. Here are some more tips on <a href="http://www.brevardcounty.us/NaturalResources/Watershed/PollutionPrevention" target="_blank">Brevard water pollution</a> issues.</li>\r\n	<li>Try <a href="http://livinggreen.ifas.ufl.edu/waste/composting.html" target="_blank">composting</a> to reduce your yard waste and create useful mulch for your yard. Also be sure to follow the <a href="http://fyn.ifas.ufl.edu/homeowners/nine_principles.htm" target="_blank">Florida-Friendly Landscaping</a> program.</li>\r\n	<li>Properly dispose of <a href="http://livinggreen.ifas.ufl.edu/waste/household_hazardous_waste.html" target="_blank">hazardous waste</a>. Improper disposal can leech chemicals into the lagoon.</li>\r\n	<li>Familiarize yourself with the details on how to <a href="http://www.brevardcounty.us/SolidWaste/RecyclingInformation" target="_blank">recycle</a> and what types of items are accepted.</li>\r\n	<li><a href="http://livinggreen.ifas.ufl.edu/water/water_conservation.html" target="_blank">Conserve Water</a> to help reduce the amount of essential fresh water removed from our aquifer each year.</li>\r\n	<li>Creating <a href="http://fyn.ifas.ufl.edu/barrels.htm" target="_blank">rain barrels</a> is a simple and effective way to conserve water around the house and yard.<a href="http://www.brevardcounty.us/NaturalResources/Watershed/PollutionPrevention">\r\n</a></li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<b>Helpful Organizations In Our Area:</b>\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li><a href="http://www.bluelifefl.org/" target="_blank">Blue Life Florida</a> is a cooperative partnership among non-profit organizations, local governments, businesses, educational institutions and residents determined to reduce the pollutant load to our nationally acclaimed bodies of water, including the Indian River Lagoon, St. Johns River, and the many tributaries that flow into them.</li>\r\n	<li><a href="http://brevard.ifas.ufl.edu/horticulture/" target="_blank">My Brevard Yard Program</a> teaches you<b> </b>how to grow a healthy landscape, protect the environment, and save money, all at the same time!</li>\r\n	<li>The <a href="http://www.sms.si.edu/SMEE/index.htm" target="_blank">Smithsonian Marine Ecosystems Exhibit</a> is a great place to visit for some educational fun.</li>\r\n	<li>The <a href="http://research.fit.edu/irlri/index.php" target="_blank">Florida Tech Indian River Lagoon Research Institute</a> has lots of great volunteer and event opportunities, and be sure to sign up for a <a href="http://camps.fit.edu/dmes/" target="_blank">Florida Tech Marine &amp; Environmental Science Summer Camp</a>, available for ages 10 and up.</li>\r\n	<li>The <a href="http://spoilislandproject.org/" target="_blank">Florida DEP Indian River Lagoon Spoil Island Project</a> has visitor information and volunteer opportunities.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<b>National Oyster Restoration Initiatives:</b>\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>The Brevard Oyster Gardening Project was modeled after many established oyster gardening projects, such as the current project in <a href="http://www.cbf.org/how-we-save-the-bay/programs-initiatives/maryland/oyster-restoration/oyster-gardening-program" target="_blank">Chesapeake Bay</a>. Give this <a href="http://blog.nature.org/science/2013/11/18/coastal-protection-and-clean-water-recognizing-the-benefits-of-oyster-reefs/?utm_source=feedburner&amp;utm_medium=email&amp;utm_campaign=Feed%3A+CoolGreenScience+%28Cool+Green+Science%29" target="_blank">Nature Conservancy article</a> a read for more information on projects across the nation.</li>\r\n</ul>', 'Additional Resources', '', 'inherit', 'closed', 'open', '', '929-revision-v1', '', '', '2014-07-10 15:10:02', '2014-07-10 15:10:02', '', 929, 'http://brevardoystergardens.org/?p=945', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
(946, 5, '2014-07-10 15:10:37', '2014-07-10 15:10:37', '<a href="http://brevardoystergardens.org/wp-content/uploads/2014/04/Home1.jpg"><img class="alignnone size-full wp-image-709" alt="Home1" src="http://brevardoystergardens.org/wp-content/uploads/2014/04/Home1.jpg" width="1000" height="771" /></a>\r\n\r\nHave additional questions? Please contact a member of the Brevard Oyster Restoration project team at Brevard Zoo:\r\n\r\n<b>Project Coordinator:Â </b><span style="line-height: 1.5;">Jody Palmer atÂ </span><a style="line-height: 1.5;" href="mailto:JPalmer@brevardzoo.org">JPalmer@brevardzoo.org</a><span style="line-height: 1.5;">Â or (321) 254-9453 x 265</span>\r\n\r\n<b>Oyster Mats:Â </b>Ryan Witzel atÂ <a href="mailto:oysterrestoration@brevardzoo.org">KFusco@brevardzoo.org</a>Â or 321.254-9453 x 377\r\n\r\n<b>Oyster Gardening:Â </b>Sammy Anderson atÂ <a href="mailto:SAnderson@brevardzoo.org">SAnderson@brevardzoo.org</a> or (321) 254-9453 x 284\r\n\r\nJohn Paul Steed atÂ <a href="mailto:JPSteed@brevardzoo.org">JPSteed@brevardzoo.org</a>Â  orÂ (321) 254-9453 x 371\r\n\r\nKarina Vega atÂ <a href="mailto:kvega@brevardzoo.org">KVega@brevardzoo.org</a>Â or (321) 506-2460\r\n\r\nAllison Arteaga atÂ <a href="mailto:aarteaga@brevardzoo.org">AArteaga@brevardzoo.org</a>Â or (321) 506-3949\r\n\r\nAlso please consider <b>making a donation</b>. Our oyster restoration projects are funded entirely through grant and donation dollars, so any contribution would be greatly appreciated. To donate, please write a check with Oyster Restoration in the memo line and mail to:\r\n\r\nBrevard Zoo\r\n8225 N. Wickham Rd.\r\nMelbourne, FL 32940.\r\n\r\nTo stay updated on all things Brevard Oyster Restoration, sign up for our <b>Oyster Gardening Newsletter</b> or <b>Oyster Mats Newsletter</b>, or join our new <a href="https://www.facebook.com/groupinvite/ATWA3BmoAkQ9xL3QSNE95-X4ALVg-bpoYKoEGUMtAANziQMKcDFXAM5dGlOLm272OwiPZydvphu5u89EwQZrG3_VLDfXs6rUICvzMJMit909KF5taJ2x6PFOd8lqD_vpQ864visjEUpyd515A4pqymu5j9ziUYA15LNWEIjn7t5krmtRe_qpn6lOxVd6U2NVuf58lEzgzIBpj6LxRgyn4zxx" target="_blank">Facebook group</a>.', 'Contact/Donate', '', 'inherit', 'closed', 'open', '', '208-revision-v1', '', '', '2014-07-10 15:10:37', '2014-07-10 15:10:37', '', 208, 'http://brevardoystergardens.org/?p=946', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
(948, 5, '2014-07-10 15:12:16', '2014-07-10 15:12:16', '<a href="http://brevardoystergardens.org/wp-content/uploads/2014/03/Watershed1.jpg"><img class="alignnone size-full wp-image-28" alt="" src="http://brevardoystergardens.org/wp-content/uploads/2014/03/Watershed1.jpg" width="1177" height="802" /></a>\r\n\r\n<b>Reduce: </b>Stormwater runoff can be detrimental to the lagoon by causing changes in nutrient and salinity levels as well as introducing pollutants, so the Brevard County Natural Resources Management Department is working on reducing the amount of stormwater discharge that enters the Indian River Lagoon. The <a href="http://www.brevardcounty.us/NaturalResources/Watershed/Home" target="_blank">Brevard County Stormwater Program</a> was created by the Board of County Commissioners in 1990, and since the early â90s, the county has invested $34 million dollars in stormwater treatment projects to either hold or purify water before it enters the lagoon. Over 450 projects have been completed, resulting in the treatment of 21,000 acres worth of stormwater, and the Brevard County Natural Resources Management Department continues to work on additional projects, the details of which can be found on their <a href="http://www.brevardcounty.us/NaturalResources/Home" target="_blank">homepage</a>.\r\n\r\nThe St. Johns River Water Management District is also responsible for managing groundwater and surface water resources in 18 counties, including Brevard County. They work directly on water supply to these counties, as well as with flood protection, water quality issues, and management of natural systems. Their <a href="http://floridaswater.com/" target="_blank">website</a> and special <a href="http://www.sjrwmd.com/irlupdate/" target="_blank">Indian River Lagoon Update</a> are excellent resources for up-to-date information on the Indian River Lagoon, including current issues and the steps being taken to find solutions. Also be sure to check out their extensive current and archivalÂ <a href="http://webapub.sjrwmd.com/agws10/hdswq/" target="_blank"><span style="text-decoration: underline;">water quality data</span></a>Â and visitÂ <a href="http://www.itsyourlagoon.com" target="_blank"><span style="text-decoration: underline;">Itâs Your Lagoon</span></a>Â for more current news and information concerning Indian River Lagoon water management initiatives.\r\n\r\n<a href="http://brevardoystergardens.org/wp-content/uploads/2014/07/Screen-Shot-2014-07-09-at-3.04.39-PM.png"><img class="alignnone size-full wp-image-857" alt="" src="http://brevardoystergardens.org/wp-content/uploads/2014/07/Screen-Shot-2014-07-09-at-3.04.39-PM.png" width="640" height="547" /></a>\r\n\r\n<b>Remove: </b>Within the Indian River Lagoon, tremendous layers of detrimental muck fill the estuary floor. This muck contains contaminants that have entered the lagoon from stormwater discharge and runoff from residential properties and other point sources. These contaminants remain in the muck, creating a layer of uninhabitable soil. This layer needs to be surgically removed from the Indian River Lagoon in order to restore essential habitat for keystone species such as seagrass. So Brevard County is working diligently to acquire the necessary funding to remove this detrimental muck from our lagoon. A great read on the topic is <a href="http://www.floridatoday.com/article/20140127/ENVIRONMENT/301270032/Muck-arch-enemy-lurks-deep-Indian-River-Lagoon" target="_blank">âMuck: The arch-enemy lurks deep in Indian River Lagoonâ</a>, written by Florida Today.<b></b>\r\n\r\n<a href="http://brevardoystergardens.org/wp-content/uploads/2014/03/Deployment21.png"><img class="alignnone size-full wp-image-74" alt="Deployment2" src="http://brevardoystergardens.org/wp-content/uploads/2014/03/Deployment21.png" width="650" height="488" /></a>\r\n\r\n<b>Research and Restore: </b>This is where the Brevard Oyster Restoration project comes in. The Brevard Zooâs Brevard Oyster Restoration project currently has two programs dedicated to restoring the Indian River Lagoon by bolstering the areaâs native oyster population. The Oyster Mats program focuses on physically rebuilding oyster reefs in the Mosquito Lagoon portion of the Indian River Lagoon, while the Oyster Gardening program is recruiting residents along the Indian River Lagoon to help provide us with data about the survivability and recruitment of oysters in Brevard County in order to determine sites for future reef rebuilding projects. Research is the foundation for any successful restoration project, so we are working very closely with academia on both the Oyster Mats and Oyster Gardening projects in order to ensure our efforts are as successful as they can be.<b></b>\r\n\r\nDr. Linda Walters of the<a href="http://www.ucf.edu/" target="_blank">Â University of Central Florida</a>Â is the science behind the Oyster Mats technique being used in Mosquito Lagoon. She and her team of researchers continue to monitor the oyster reefs each year, collecting data concerning the survivability, growth, recruitment and predation of the oysters in Mosquito Lagoon. For the Oyster Gardening project, Â all of the data our citizen scientists collect throughout the project will be entered into a database where it can then be analyzed for further interpretation.', 'Steps To Saving The Lagoon', '', 'inherit', 'closed', 'open', '', '851-revision-v1', '', '', '2014-07-10 15:12:16', '2014-07-10 15:12:16', '', 851, 'http://brevardoystergardens.org/?p=948', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
(949, 5, '2014-07-10 15:17:05', '2014-07-10 15:17:05', '<img title="gallery link=&quot;file&quot; columns=&quot;5&quot; ids=&quot;1207,1199,1205,1201,1200&quot;" src="http://brevardoystergardens.org/wp-includes/js/tinymce/plugins/wpgallery/img/t.gif" alt="" />\r\n\r\n[gallery columns="5" link="file" ids="1207,1199,1205,1201,1200"]\r\n\r\nTheÂ Brevard Oyster Gardening project, launched by Brevard Zoo in partnership with the Brevard County Natural Resources Management Office, encourages the community to get involved with repairing damages to the lagoon. Inspired by the oyster reef restoration work Â Brevard Zoo has been doing with UCF in Mosquito Lagoon, the Oyster Gardening Project has expanded reef restoration intoÂ the more challenging Brevard County portion of theÂ Indian River Lagoon by first collecting data to identify areas with high rates of oyster survivability and recruitment that are good candidate locations for Â reef restoration projects.Â Oysters grown through the Oyster Gardening program are then used to populate Brevard County restoration reefs, the first of which were built in the fall of 2014, accomplishing both habitat restoration and oyster reintroduction...\r\n\r\n<img class="alignnone  wp-image-716" src="http://brevardoystergardens.org/wp-content/uploads/2014/04/Home7.jpg" alt="Home7" width="974" height="773" />\r\n\r\nIn order to grow oysters and collect the data used for reef building, the Brevard County Commissioners funded the project with $150,000 to supply a small staff and provide the necessary equipment to train volunteers in Brevard County to become âoyster gardeners.â The project relies entirely onÂ <a href="https://mapalist.com/Public/pm.aspx?mapid=502080" target="_blank">these volunteers</a>Â living along the shores of the Indian River Lagoon who agree to hang oyster habitats from their docks and then care for and monitor their oysters to collect data on the growth, survivability, and recruitment of oysters in their area, all of which gets entered into a database on a weekly basis for a period of about six Â months.\r\n\r\n<img class="alignnone  wp-image-596" src="http://brevardoystergardens.org/wp-content/uploads/2014/03/Oysters_Kiwanis-Park-361.jpg" alt="Oysters_Kiwanis Park 36" width="3312" height="2704" />\r\n\r\nOyster gardeners first attend a special workshop where they learn all the details of the program and build their own oyster habitats. Later, they receive oyster shells covered with live spat (juvenile oysters), which they place into their habitats and then deploy from their docks, beginning the care and data collection process. To ensure the greatest probability of success, the oyster spat used in the Oyster Gardening project are spawned from a local brood stock near Sebastian, FL. Their spawning takes place at the Florida Oceanographic Society, in a hatchery dedicated to the reproduction of the Eastern Oyster. Using a local population of oysters from Brevard County to parent our oyster spat will keep future generations of oysters in restored populations genetically similar to those that once made up the areaâs original population.\r\n\r\n[gallery columns="5" link="file" ids="656,658,654,603,1076"]\r\n\r\nClick link to read the <a href="http://brevardoystergardens.org/wp-content/uploads/2015/02/2014-Oyster-Gardening-Annual-Report.FINAL_.pdf" target="_blank">Oyster Gardening 2014 Annual Report</a>.\r\n\r\n<strong>Want to learn more about our reef-building process? Check out this video:Â </strong>\r\n\r\n<iframe width="853" height="480" src="https://www.youtube.com/embed/cfI0234h36g" frameborder="0" allowfullscreen></iframe>\r\n\r\n', 'Oyster Gardening Details', '', 'publish', 'closed', 'open', '', 'oyster-gardening-details', '', '', '2015-10-09 20:23:45', '2015-10-09 20:23:45', '', 0, 'http://brevardoystergardens.org/?page_id=949', 0, 'page', '', 0),
(950, 5, '2014-07-10 15:17:05', '2014-07-10 15:17:05', '', 'Oyster Gardening Details', '', 'inherit', 'closed', 'open', '', '949-revision-v1', '', '', '2014-07-10 15:17:05', '2014-07-10 15:17:05', '', 949, 'http://brevardoystergardens.org/?p=950', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
(951, 5, '2014-07-10 15:17:56', '2014-07-10 15:17:56', '<a href="http://brevardoystergardens.org/wp-content/uploads/2014/04/Home7.jpg"><img class="alignnone size-full wp-image-716" alt="Home7" src="http://brevardoystergardens.org/wp-content/uploads/2014/04/Home7.jpg" width="974" height="773" /></a>\r\n\r\nTheÂ Brevard Oyster Gardening project, launched by Brevard Zoo in partnership with the Brevard County Natural Resources Management Office, is encouraging the community to get involved with the process of repairing damages to the lagoon. Inspired by the oyster reef restoration work that Brevard Zoo has been doing with UCF in Mosquito Lagoon, the Oyster Gardening Project seeks to expand reef restoration intoÂ Brevard Countyâs portion of theÂ Indian River Lagoon by first identifying areas with high rates of oyster survivability and recruitment that are good candidate locations for a future reef restoration project.\r\n\r\nIn order to collect the necessary data, the Brevard County Commissioners funded the project with $150,000 to supply a small staff and provide the necessary equipment to train volunteers in Brevard County to become âoyster gardeners.â The project relies almost entirely on <a href="http://mapalist.com/Public/pm.aspx?mapid=435233" target="_blank">these volunteers</a> living along the shores of the Indian River Lagoon who agree to hang oyster habitats from their docks and then monitor those habitats to collect data on the growth, survivability, and recruitment of oysters in their area, all of which gets entered into a database on a weekly basis for a period of about six to seven months.\r\n\r\n<a href="http://brevardoystergardens.org/wp-content/uploads/2014/03/Oysters_Kiwanis-Park-361.jpg"><img class="alignnone size-full wp-image-596" alt="Oysters_Kiwanis Park 36" src="http://brevardoystergardens.org/wp-content/uploads/2014/03/Oysters_Kiwanis-Park-361.jpg" width="3312" height="2704" /></a>\r\n\r\nOyster gardeners first attend a special workshop where they learn all the details of the program and build their own oyster habitats. Later, they receive oyster shells covered with live spat (juvenile oysters), which they place into their habitats and then deploy from their docks, beginning the data collection process. To ensure the greatest probability of success, the oyster spat used in the Oyster Gardening project are spawned from a local brood stock near Sebastian, FL. Their spawning takes place at the Florida Oceanographic Society, in a hatchery dedicated to the reproduction of the Eastern Oyster. Using a local population of oysters from Brevard County to parent these oyster spat will keep future generations of oysters in potential restored populations genetically similar to those that once made up the areaâs original population.\r\n\r\n[gallery ids="658,654,656"]', 'Oyster Gardening Details', '', 'inherit', 'closed', 'open', '', '949-revision-v1', '', '', '2014-07-10 15:17:56', '2014-07-10 15:17:56', '', 949, 'http://brevardoystergardens.org/?p=951', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
