nt and archivalÂ <a href="http://webapub.sjrwmd.com/agws10/hdswq/" target="_blank"><span style="text-decoration: underline;">water quality data</span></a>Â and visitÂ <a href="http://www.itsyourlagoon.com" target="_blank"><span style="text-decoration: underline;">Itâs Your Lagoon</span></a>Â for more current news and information concerning Indian River Lagoon water management initiatives.\r\n\r\n<img class="alignnone  wp-image-857" alt="" src="http://brevardoystergardens.org/wp-content/uploads/2014/07/Screen-Shot-2014-07-09-at-3.04.39-PM.png" width="640" height="547" />\r\n\r\n<b>Remove: </b>Within the Indian River Lagoon, tremendous layers of detrimental muck fill the estuary floor. This muck contains contaminants that have entered the lagoon from stormwater discharge and runoff from residential properties and other point sources. These contaminants remain in the muck, creating a layer of uninhabitable soil. This layer needs to be surgically removed from the Indian River Lagoon in order to restore essential habitat for keystone species such as seagrass. So Brevard County is working diligently to acquire the necessary funding to remove this detrimental muck from our lagoon. A great read on the topic is <a href="http://www.floridatoday.com/article/20140127/ENVIRONMENT/301270032/Muck-arch-enemy-lurks-deep-Indian-River-Lagoon" target="_blank">âMuck: The arch-enemy lurks deep in Indian River Lagoonâ</a>, written by Florida Today.<b></b>\r\n\r\n<img class="alignnone  wp-image-74" alt="Deployment2" src="http://brevardoystergardens.org/wp-content/uploads/2014/03/Deployment21.png" width="650" height="488" />\r\n\r\n<b>Research and Restore: </b>This is where the Brevard Oyster Restoration project comes in. The Brevard Zooâs Brevard Oyster Restoration project currently has two programs dedicated to restoring the Indian River Lagoon by bolstering the areaâs native oyster population. The Oyster Mats program focuses on physically rebuilding oyster reefs in the Mosquito Lagoon portion of the Indian River Lagoon, while the Oyster Gardening program is recruiting residents along the Indian River Lagoon to help provide us with data about the survivability and recruitment of oysters in Brevard County in order to determine sites for future reef rebuilding projects. Research is the foundation for any successful restoration project, so we are working very closely with academia on both the Oyster Mats and Oyster Gardening projects in order to ensure our efforts are as successful as they can be.<b></b>\r\n\r\nDr. Linda Walters of the<a href="http://www.ucf.edu/" target="_blank">Â University of Central Florida</a>Â is the science behind the Oyster Mats technique being used in Mosquito Lagoon. She and her team of researchers continue to monitor the oyster reefs each year, collecting data concerning the survivability, growth, recruitment and predation of the oysters in Mosquito Lagoon. For the Oyster Gardening project, Â all of the data our citizen scientists collect throughout the project will be entered into a database where it can then be analyzed for further interpretation.', 'Saving The Lagoon', '', 'inherit', 'closed', 'open', '', '851-revision-v1', '', '', '2014-08-25 17:41:53', '2014-08-25 17:41:53', '', 851, 'http://brevardoystergardens.org/851-revision-v1/', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
