here they learn all the details of the program and build their own oyster habitats. Later, they receive oyster shells covered with live spat (juvenile oysters), which they place into their habitats and then deploy from their docks, beginning the data collection process. To ensure the greatest probability of success, the oyster spat used in the Oyster Gardening project are spawned from a local brood stock near Sebastian, FL. Their spawning takes place at the Florida Oceanographic Society, in a hatchery dedicated to the reproduction of the Eastern Oyster. Using a local population of oysters from Brevard County to parent these oyster spat will keep future generations of oysters in potential restored populations genetically similar to those that once made up the areaâs original population.\r\n\r\n[gallery ids="658,654,656"]', 'Oyster Gardening Details', '', 'inherit', 'closed', 'open', '', '949-revision-v1', '', '', '2014-07-18 15:03:21', '2014-07-18 15:03:21', '', 949, 'http://brevardoystergardens.org/?p=997', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
(998, 5, '2014-07-18 15:08:54', '2014-07-18 15:08:54', 'Oyster Gardening workshops are <b>only for qualified individuals</b> and require reservations in advance. If you are approved for a workshop, we will provide all necessary supplies, so just plan to arrive 15 minutes early for sign-in, then stay throughout the entirety of the two-and-a-half hour workshop. Â Oyster Gardening is a great activity to get the whole family involved with at home, but please note that gardening workshops are primarily directed toward adults...\r\n\r\n<a href="http://brevardoystergardens.org/wp-content/uploads/2014/04/home8.jpg"><img class="alignnone size-full wp-image-717" alt="home8" src="http://brevardoystergardens.org/wp-content/uploads/2014/04/home8.jpg" width="706" height="625" /></a>\r\n\r\n<b><span style="text-decoration: underline;">HOW DO I QUALIFY FOR A WORKSHOP?</span></b>\r\n\r\nOnly those who are qualified to be either an Oyster Gardener or Oyster Buddy may attend an Oyster Gardening workshop. The requirements for both designations are as follows:\r\n\r\n<b>Oyster Gardener</b>\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>Has a dock on the open Indian River Lagoon (not a canal) in Brevard County. Community docks for homeowners associations and condos can also be eligible, but check out these special <a href="http://brevardoystergardens.org/wp-content/uploads/2014/06/Community-Docks-Guidelines.docx">guidelines</a> first.</li>\r\n	<li>Can commit one to two hours of time per week to cleaning and monitoring oyster habitats and entering findings into a database</li>\r\n	<li>Not planning to be out of town for extended periods of time over the next six to seven months</li>\r\n	<li>Can lift 30 lbs</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<b>Oyster Buddy</b>\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>Able to temporarily fill in for traveling or sick Oyster Gardeners by committing one to two hours per week to maintaining and monitoring their habitats for them</li>\r\n	<li>Has access to a reliable means of transportation to Oyster Gardening sites</li>\r\n	<li>Can lift 30 lbs</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<a href="http://brevardoystergardens.org/wp-content/uploads/2014/04/Home9.jpg"><img class="alignnone size-full wp-image-718" alt="Home9" src="http://brevardoystergardens.org/wp-content/uploads/2014/04/Home9.jpg" width="707" height="643" /></a>\r\n\r\n<b>IF YOU MEET THE REQUIREMENTS</b> to be either an Oyster Gardener or Oyster Buddy, please <a href="http://brevardoystergardens.org/?page_id=970">sign up </a>for an Oyster Gardening workshop. (<em>Only one registration is necessary per family/group</em>).\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n&nbsp;', 'Oyster Gardening Workshops', '', 'inherit', 'closed', 'open', '', '903-revision-v1', '', '', '2014-07-18 15:08:54', '2014-07-18 15:08:54', '', 903, 'http://brevardoystergardens.org/?p=998', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
(1000, 5, '2015-10-09 20:22:42', '2015-10-09 20:22:42', '<img title="gallery link=&quot;file&quot; columns=&quot;5&quot; ids=&quot;1207,1199,1205,1201,1200&quot;" src="http://brevardoystergardens.org/wp-includes/js/tinymce/plugins/wpgallery/img/t.gif" alt="" />\n\n[gallery columns="5" link="file" ids="1207,1199,1205,1201,1200"]\n\nTheÂ Brevard Oyster Gardening project, launched by Brevard Zoo in partnership with the Brevard County Natural Resources Management Office, encourages the community to get involved with repairing damages to the lagoon. Inspired by the oyster reef restoration work Â Brevard Zoo has been doing with UCF in Mosquito Lagoon, the Oyster Gardening Project has expanded reef restoration intoÂ the more challenging Brevard County portion of theÂ Indian River Lagoon by first collecting data to identify areas with high rates of oyster survivability and recruitment that are good candidate locations for Â reef restoration projects.Â Oysters grown through the Oyster Gardening program are then used to populate Brevard County restoration reefs, the first of which were built in the fall of 2014, accomplishing both habitat restoration and oyster reintroduction...\n\n<img class="alignnone  wp-image-716" src="http://brevardoystergardens.org/wp-content/uploads/2014/04/Home7.jpg" alt="Home7" width="974" height="773" />\n\nIn order to grow oysters and collect the data used for reef building, the Brevard County Commissioners funded the project with $150,000 to supply a small staff and provide the necessary equipment to train volunteers in Brevard County to become âoyster gardeners.â The project relies entirely onÂ <a href="https://mapalist.com/Public/pm.aspx?mapid=502080" target="_blank">these volunteers</a>Â living along the shores of the Indian River Lagoon who agree to hang oyster habitats from their docks and then care for and monitor their oysters to collect data on the growth, survivability, and recruitment of oysters in their area, all of which gets entered into a database on a weekly basis for a period of about six Â months.\n\n<img class="alignnone  wp-image-596" src="http://brevardoystergardens.org/wp-content/uploads/2014/03/Oysters_Kiwanis-Park-361.jpg" alt="Oysters_Kiwanis Park 36" width="3312" height="2704" />\n\nOyster gardeners first attend a special workshop where they learn all the details of the program and build their own oyster habitats. Later, they receive oyster shells covered with live spat (juvenile oysters), which they place into their habitats and then deploy from their docks, beginning the care and data collection process. To ensure the greatest probability of success, the oyster spat used in the Oyster Gardening project are spawned from a local brood stock near Sebastian, FL. Their spawning takes place at the Florida Oceanographic Society, in a hatchery dedicated to the reproduction of the Eastern Oyster. Using a local population of oysters from Brevard County to parent our oyster spat will keep future generations of oysters in restored populations genetically similar to those that once made up the areaâs original population.\n\n[gallery columns="5" link="file" ids="656,658,654,603,1076"]\n\nClick link to read the <a href="http://brevardoystergardens.org/wp-content/uploads/2015/02/2014-Oyster-Gardening-Annual-Report.FINAL_.pdf" target="_blank">Oyster Gardening 2014 Annual Report</a>.\n\n<strong>Want to learn more about our reef-building process? Check out this video:Â </strong>\n\n<iframe width="560" height="315" src="https://www.youtube.com/embed/cfI0234h36g" frameborder="0" allowfullscreen></iframe>\n\n', 'Oyster Gardening Details', '', 'inherit', 'closed', 'open', '', '949-autosave-v1', '', '', '2015-10-09 20:22:42', '2015-10-09 20:22:42', '', 949, 'http://brevardoystergardens.org/?p=1000', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
