(1041, 5, '2014-08-25 17:31:56', '2014-08-25 17:31:56', 'Have you seen our new commercial on Brighthouse Networks?\r\n\r\n<iframe src="//www.youtube.com/embed/8s0WGxu_ZL0" height="480" width="853" allowfullscreen="" frameborder="0"></iframe>\r\n\r\n(<a href="http://brevardoystergardens.org/oyster-gardening-workshops/" target="_blank">Click here if you''re a lagoon-front resident interested in becoming an oyster gardener</a>)\r\n\r\n(<a href="http://brevardoystergardens.org/help-make-oyster-mats/" target="_blank">Click here if you''re interested in making oyster mats</a>)\r\n\r\n<strong>ABOUT BREVARD OYSTER RESTORATION:</strong>\r\n\r\nSpanning 156 miles and five Florida counties, the Indian River Lagoon is one of the most biologically diverse estuaries in the country, providing a home for more than 4,000 species of plants and animals. The vast majority of this waterway, which includes the Mosquito Lagoon area and both the Banana and Indian rivers, is located here in Brevard County, providing our community with a one-of-a-kind ecological and recreational treasure that also has an estimated economic value of $3.7 billon per year.\r\n\r\n<a href="http://brevardoystergardens.org/wp-content/uploads/2014/04/Screen-Shot-2014-07-09-at-4.31.19-PM.png"><img class="alignnone size-full wp-image-884" alt="" src="http://brevardoystergardens.org/wp-content/uploads/2014/04/Screen-Shot-2014-07-09-at-4.31.19-PM.png" width="940" height="623" /></a>\r\n\r\nHowever, in recent years, the lagoon has seen increasing threats to its water quality and biological diversity. Continuous inputs of pollution have overloaded the estuary, resulting in algal blooms and the deaths of wildlife. But Brevard Zoo recognized the importance of using the oysterâs natural ability to filter water as a way to improve the water quality of the Indian River Lagoon.\r\n\r\nThe Eastern oyster, Crassotrea virginica, was once found in abundance along the Indian River Lagoon but has now disappeared from many portions of the waterway. The native oyster population was decimated by a combination of factors; including habitat loss, overharvesting, pollution, reduced water quality, disease and boat wakes. Oysters are an essential part of the Indian River lagoon ecosystem for many reasons. They are a keystone species that numerous other species depend on for food and protection. Oysters are also gregarious, which means that individuals clump together, creating natural reefs that help prevent erosion.\r\n\r\n<a href="http://brevardoystergardens.org/wp-content/uploads/2014/03/why31.jpg"><img class="alignnone size-full wp-image-684" alt="why3" src="http://brevardoystergardens.org/wp-content/uploads/2014/03/why31.jpg" width="803" height="504" /></a>\r\n\r\nBut most importantly, oysters are filter feeders, which means that they consume organic material present in the waters of the lagoon, thereby cleaning the water. In fact, one average adult oyster can filter up to 50 gallons of water per day. Imagine how many gallons of filtered water this would add up to over an oysterâs 20 year life span!Â Their filtering abilities help to reduce the amount of algae and muck floating in the river, and the resulting improved water clarity and light penetration is especially important for sea grass, another keystone species in the Indian River Lagoon.\r\n\r\nSo, in 2005, Brevard Zoo partnered with the University of Central Florida to restore oyster reefs in the Mosquito Lagoon portion of the Indian River Lagoon.Â The reefs are created using a quilt-like pattern of oyster mats, which was developed by Dr. Linda Walters. Since that time, over 36,000 mats have been made and deployed, establishing 63 new oyster reefs, thanks to the help of over 36,000 volunteers.\r\n\r\n<a href="http://brevardoystergardens.org/wp-content/uploads/2014/04/Home4.jpg"><img class="alignnone size-full wp-image-712" alt="Home4" src="http://brevardoystergardens.org/wp-content/uploads/2014/04/Home4.jpg" width="1430" height="1073" /></a>\r\n\r\nBrevard Zoo has also recently partnered with Brevard County to launch the Oyster Gardening Project. This is a community-based project that relies on the efforts of citizen scientists to collect data on oyster survivability in the Indian River Lagoon. Residents living along the lagoon volunteer to create oyster habitats and deploy them off of their docks. The habitats are then populated with living oyster spats (attached oyster larvae) and are monitored weekly for signs of recruitment and survivability. This data will be used to determine locations for future large-scale oyster reef restoration projects similar to the work currently being done in Mosquito Lagoon.\r\n\r\n<b>For more information about the issues affecting the Indian River Lagoon, please refer to the following articles:</b>\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li><a href="http://www.nytimes.com/2013/08/08/us/deaths-of-manatees-dolphins-and-pelicans-point-to-estuary-at-risk.html?_r=0" target="_blank">âDeaths of Manatees, Dolphins and Pelicans Point to Estuary at Riskâ</a><a href="http://www.nytimes.com/2013/08/08/us/deaths-of-manatees-dolphins-and-pelicans-point-to-estuary-at-risk.html?_r=0">-Â </a>New York Times</li>\r\n	<li><a href="http://www.floridatoday.com/article/20130918/NEWS01/309180014/Algae-related-fish-kills-plague-Indian-River-Lagoon" target="_blank">âAlgae-related fish kills plague Indian River Lagoonâ</a>- Florida Today</li>\r\n	<li>Letter from Keith Winsten, Executive Director of Brevard ZooÂ <a href="http://www.floridatoday.com/article/20130903/NEWS01/309030001/Keith-Winsten-Lagoon-needs-our-help-now-survive" target="_blank">âLagoon needs our help now to surviveâ</a>Â - Florida Today</li>\r\n	<li><a href="http://articles.orlandosentinel.com/2014-02-01/news/os-manatee-deaths-indian-river-20140201_1_indian-river-lagoon-katie-tripp-dead-manatees" target="_blank">âManatee deaths unsolved amid effort to reverse Indian River collapseâ</a>Â - Orlando Sentinel</li>\r\n	<li><a href="http://www.floridatoday.com/article/20131126/NEWS01/311260012/Living-dock-might-help-heal-lagoon" target="_blank">âGirl Scoutsâ Living Dock Might Help Heal Indian River Lagoonâ</a>âFlorida Today</li>\r\n	<li><a href="http://www.wesh.com/indian-river-lagoon-oyster-experiment-shows-promise/25521854#!FmnHB" target="_blank">âIndian River Lagoon Oyster Experiment Shows Promiseâ</a>â Wesh Orlando</li>\r\n	<li><a href="http://www.floridatoday.com/story/news/local/environment/lagoon/2014/05/03/indian-river-lagoon-went-wrong/8672245/?sf25781894=%5B%271%27%5D" target="_blank">âIndian River Lagoon: What went wrong?â</a>âFlorida Today</li>\r\n	<li><a href="http://creative.news-journalonline.com/troubledwater/" target="_blank">âTroubled Water: The Indian River Lagoon in Perilâ</a>-Daytona Beach News-Journal</li>\r\n	<li><a href="http://www.floridatoday.com/story/news/local/environment/2014/08/06/cities-ponder-new-ponds-higher-fees-to-meet-lagoon-pollution-limits/13670487/" target="_blank">"Cleaning Indian River Lagoon will cost $1.4 billion"</a> âFlorida Today</li>\r\n</ul>', 'Home', '', 'inherit', 'closed', 'open', '', '587-revision-v1', '', '', '2014-08-25 17:31:56', '2014-08-25 17:31:56', '', 587, 'http://brevardoystergardens.org/587-revision-v1/', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
(1049, 5, '2014-08-25 17:45:56', '2014-08-25 17:45:56', '<i>Over the years, we have seen a tremendous decline in Brevard Countyâs ecologically important oyster population for several reasonsâ¦</i>\r\n\r\n[caption id="attachment_689" align="alignnone" width="1113"]<img class="size-full wp-image-689" alt="OVERHARVESTING: Oysters are a delicious meal for both animals and humans alike, but when they are continuously harvested at a rate faster than they can reproduce, the natural population canât keep up, and their numbers begin to decline." src="http://brevardoystergardens.org/wp-content/uploads/2014/03/threats31.png" width="1113" height="376" /> OVERHARVESTING: Oysters are a delicious meal for both animals and humans alike, but when they are continuously harvested at a rate faster than they can reproduce, the natural population canât keep up, and their numbers begin to decline.[/caption]\r\n\r\n[caption id="attachment_864" align="alignnone" width="1024"]<img class=" wp-image-864 " alt="HABITAT LOSS: Oysters are intertidal species, meaning they live in areas along the shoreline that experience a natural fluctuation of tides. These areas are popular locations for homes, businesses and marinas, so as coastal development increases, the available habitat for an oyster reef diminishes." src="http://brevardoystergardens.org/wp-content/uploads/2014/07/Blue_heron_Indian_River_Lagoon_Jensen_Beach_Florida_052.jpg" width="1024" height="768" /> HABITAT LOSS: Oysters are intertidal species, meaning they live in areas along the shoreline that experience a natural fluctuation of tides. These areas are popular locations for homes, businesses and marinas, so as coastal development increases, the available habitat for an oyster reef diminishes.[/caption]\r\n\r\n[caption id="attachment_865" align="alignnone" width="640"]<img class=" wp-image-865 " alt="REDUCED WATER QUALITY: Oysters are tremendous filter feeders, but they arenât able to filter out the overwhelming amount of pollution being introduced into the Indian River Lagoon. They can filter out suspended particles at an astonishing rate of approximately two gallons of water per hour, but unfortunately, solid waste and complex chemical compounds such as fertilizers and pesticides inhibit their filter feeding abilities." src="http://brevardoystergardens.org/wp-content/uploads/2014/07/6442817047_a35459c6b9_z.jpg" width="640" height="480" /> REDUCED WATER QUALITY: Oysters are tremendous filter feeders, but they arenât able to filter out the overwhelming amount of pollution being introduced into the Indian River Lagoon. They can filter out suspended particles at an astonishing rate of approximately two gallons of water per hour, but unfortunately, solid waste and complex chemical compounds such as fertilizers and pesticides inhibit their filter feeding abilities.[/caption]\r\n\r\n[caption id="attachment_691" align="alignnone" width="672"]<img class=" wp-image-691 " alt="DISEASE: Just like we get colds and flus, oysters suffer from two diseases that are specific to them: Dermo and MSX. These particular diseases can spread and cause the oyster population to decline as a result." src="http://brevardoystergardens.org/wp-content/uploads/2014/03/threats61.jpg" width="672" height="372" /> DISEASE: Just like we get colds and flus, oysters suffer from two diseases that are specific to them: Dermo and MSX. These particular diseases can spread and cause the oyster population to decline as a result.[/caption]\r\n\r\n[caption id="attachment_692" align="alignnone" width="672"]<img class=" wp-image-692 " alt="BOAT WAKES: Large waves produced by a moving vessel on the Indian River Lagoon can dislodge oysters from the reef. Once the oysters are off the reef, they canât just walk right back on to it and live happily ever after. Dislodged oysters will roll in the waves, ultimately forming piles in the shallow water, where they will dry out and die. The resulting large piles of oyster shells are referred to as dead margins." src="http://brevardoystergardens.org/wp-content/uploads/2014/03/threats71.jpg" width="672" height="372" /> BOAT WAKES: Large waves produced by a moving vessel on the Indian River Lagoon can dislodge oysters from the reef. Once the oysters are off the reef, they canât just walk right back on to it and live happily ever after. Dislodged oysters will roll in the waves, ultimately forming piles in the shallow water, where they will dry out and die. The resulting large piles of oyster shells are referred to as dead margins.[/caption]\r\n\r\n<i>But oysters are considered a keystone species in the Indian River Lagoon, meaning they hold a vital role in keeping the ecosystem balanced. If a keystone species is removed, it negatively affects many other species. So, although they are small in size, oysters are very important to the Indian River Lagoon ecosystem for several reasonsâ¦</i>\r\n\r\n<img alt="functions2" src="http://brevardoystergardens.org/wp-content/uploads/2014/03/functions21.jpg" width="895" height="699" />\r\n\r\n<strong>Food:</strong>Â Oyster reefs are a food source for a wide variety of species in the Indian River Lagoon that feed directly on the oysters as well as on the critters living on and around oyster reefs.\r\n\r\n<strong>Habitat:</strong>Â Fondly referred to as the âliving razor blade,â oyster reefs provide plenty of hiding places for small critters and juvenile fishes. These tight crevices are a perfect nursery for small fish, and oyster reefs also provide a buffet of food, including algae, crustaceans and phytoplankton, in the surrounding habitat.\r\n\r\n<strong>Erosion Prevention:</strong>Â Since oysters live along the shoreline, oyster reefs can help to prevent erosion. As damaging waves travel toward the coast, they first hit oyster reefs, which dissipate the wave energy, diminishing its effects on the shore. This decreases the amount of sediment being pulled away from the shoreline, therefore decreasing erosion.\r\n\r\n<strong>Filter Feeding:Â </strong>Oysters use their gills to pull in water from the lagoon filled with suspended particles, such as algae and muck. Oysters use those particles to provide themselves with nutrients and minerals, and after an oyster has consumed all of the viable nutrients in a particular bit of water, it will spit it back out as cleaner and clearer lagoon water. Oysters filter feed around the clock at a rate of nearly 50 gallons of water per day. Thatâs more than 1,500 times their body volume. With this tremendous filtering ability, established oyster reefs are essential for improved water quality, which will result in a healthier Indian River Lagoon.\r\n\r\n<iframe src="//player.vimeo.com/video/100847263" height="479" width="853" allowfullscreen="" frameborder="0"></iframe>\r\n\r\n<a href="http://vimeo.com/100847263">Oyster Filtration Timelapse</a> from <a href="http://vimeo.com/elisehugus">Elise Hugus</a> on <a href="https://vimeo.com">Vimeo</a>.\r\n\r\n<i>For more information on oysters, check out the Loxahatchee River Districtâs additionalÂ <a href="http://www.loxahatcheeriver.org/rivercenterflash/slides.html" target="_blank">educational materials.</a></i>', 'Why Oysters?', '', 'inherit', 'closed', 'open', '', '140-revision-v1', '', '', '2014-08-25 17:45:56', '2014-08-25 17:45:56', '', 140, 'http://brevardoystergardens.org/140-revision-v1/', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
