(1228, 5, '2014-12-03 19:29:29', '2014-12-03 19:29:29', '<strong>REFERENCE DOCUMENTS</strong>\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li><a href="http://brevardoystergardens.org/wp-content/uploads/2014/07/Version2-_Oyster-Gardening-Presentation_2014.pdf">Oyster Gardening Presentation</a></li>\r\n	<li><a href="http://brevardoystergardens.org/wp-content/uploads/2014/07/Brevard-Oyster-Gardening-Manual_Version-2_2014.pdf">Brevard Oyster Gardening Manual</a></li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<strong>HABITAT DEPLOYMENT TIPS</strong>\r\n\r\n<iframe src="//www.youtube.com/embed/TGYhsGeso4I" height="480" width="853" allowfullscreen="" frameborder="0"></iframe>\r\n\r\n<strong style="line-height: 1.5;">HABITAT MAINTENANCE TIPS</strong>\r\n\r\n<iframe src="//www.youtube.com/embed/0MoHFOpb3II" height="480" width="853" allowfullscreen="" frameborder="0"></iframe>\r\n\r\n<strong>OYSTER SPAT IDENTIFICATION GUIDES</strong>\r\n\r\nOyster spat 3 weeks post-distribution:\r\n\r\n[gallery link="file" ids="740,739,737"]\r\n\r\nOyster spat time progression:\r\n\r\n[gallery columns="5" ids="1129,1130,1131,1132,1133"]\r\n\r\nOyster spat under fouling:\r\n\r\n[gallery columns="4" link="file" ids="843,844,845,849"]\r\n\r\n<strong>FOULING LEVEL DESIGNATION:</strong>\r\n\r\n[gallery link="file" ids="743,1122,1125"]\r\n\r\n<strong>OYSTER COHABITANTS IDENTIFICATION GUIDES</strong>\r\n\r\nOyster friends:\r\n\r\n[gallery link="file" columns="5" ids="773,775,727,817,819,820,1115,1116,1119,1120"]\r\n\r\nOyster foes:\r\n\r\n[gallery link="file" columns="5" ids="728,726,725,722,721,768,772,771,770,1106,1108,1111,1112,1113"]\r\n\r\nFound something in your habitat that you don''t see here? Look it up in the Smithsonian Marine Station''sÂ <a href="http://www.sms.si.edu/irlspec/SpeciesImageGallery.htm" target="_blank">Indian River Lagoon Species Database</a>.\r\n\r\n<strong>DATA ENTRY TIPS:</strong>\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>Most fields in our database accept properly formatted numerals only, with the exception of "comment", "fouling load," and "other" fields.</li>\r\n	<li>Distances are assumed to be in feet, times are assumed to be in minutes, and weights are assumed to be in pounds, so do not type units of measure, or you will receive an error message.</li>\r\n	<li>Check box fields designate an affirmative answer if they are checked and a negative answer if they are not.</li>\r\n	<li>Dates are to be typed in the form dd/mm/yyyy, and phone numbers with area code are to be separated with periods instead of dashes.</li>\r\n	<li>The fields for Â yellow and green habitats are left over from a previous round of gardening and do not apply, so please leave them blank.</li>\r\n	<li>Please refer to the examples below...</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<strong>"Habitat Information" section:</strong>\r\n\r\n[caption id="attachment_1224" align="alignnone" width="1024"]<a href="http://brevardoystergardens.org/wp-content/uploads/2014/07/Screen-Shot-2014-12-03-at-1.43.04-PM1.png"><img class=" wp-image-1224 " alt="Habitat Information" src="http://brevardoystergardens.org/wp-content/uploads/2014/07/Screen-Shot-2014-12-03-at-1.43.04-PM1-1024x663.png" width="1024" height="663" /></a> This section records basic information about when and where you initially deployed your habitats. You will only need to fill it out once at the start of the program.[/caption]\r\n\r\n<strong>"Habitat Observations" section: </strong>\r\n\r\n[caption id="attachment_1217" align="alignnone" width="1024"]<a href="http://brevardoystergardens.org/wp-content/uploads/2014/07/Screen-Shot-2014-12-03-at-1.45.22-PM.png"><img class=" wp-image-1217   " alt="Habitat observations" src="http://brevardoystergardens.org/wp-content/uploads/2014/07/Screen-Shot-2014-12-03-at-1.45.22-PM-1024x711.png" width="1024" height="711" /></a> This section tracks changes to your habitats over time, such as growth of oysters and fouling, organisms present in your habitat, and the development of natural recruitment . You should enter data in this section each week as you perform your habitat maintenance.[/caption]', 'Oyster Gardening Resources', '', 'inherit', 'closed', 'open', '', '906-revision-v1', '', '', '2014-12-03 19:29:29', '2014-12-03 19:29:29', '', 906, 'http://brevardoystergardens.org/906-revision-v1/', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
(1242, 5, '2014-12-22 15:12:36', '2014-12-22 15:12:36', '[gallery link="file" columns="5" ids="1207,1199,1205,1201,1200"]\r\n\r\nTheÂ Brevard Oyster Gardening project, launched by Brevard Zoo in partnership with the Brevard County Natural Resources Management Office, encourages the community to get involved with repairing damages to the lagoon. Inspired by the oyster reef restoration work Â Brevard Zoo has been doing with UCF in Mosquito Lagoon, the Oyster Gardening Project has expanded reef restoration intoÂ the more challenging Brevard County portion of theÂ Indian River Lagoon by first collecting data to identify areas with high rates of oyster survivability and recruitment that are good candidate locations for Â reef restoration projects.\r\n\r\nOysters grown through the Oyster Gardening program are then used to populate Brevard County''s new restoration reefs, the first of which were built in the fall of 2014, accomplishing both habitat restoration and oyster reintroduction...\r\n\r\n<img class="alignnone  wp-image-716" alt="Home7" src="http://brevardoystergardens.org/wp-content/uploads/2014/04/Home7.jpg" width="974" height="773" />\r\n\r\nIn order to grow oysters and collect the data used for reef placement, the Brevard County Commissioners funded the project with $150,000 to supply a small staff and provide the necessary equipment to train volunteers in Brevard County to become âoyster gardeners.â The project relies entirely onÂ <a href="https://mapalist.com/Public/pm.aspx?mapid=435233" target="_blank">these volunteers</a>Â living along the shores of the Indian River Lagoon who agree to hang oyster habitats from their docks and then care for and monitor their oysters to collect data on the growth, survivability, and recruitment of oysters in their area, all of which gets entered into a database on a weekly basis for a period of about six Â months.\r\n\r\n<img class="alignnone  wp-image-596" alt="Oysters_Kiwanis Park 36" src="http://brevardoystergardens.org/wp-content/uploads/2014/03/Oysters_Kiwanis-Park-361.jpg" width="3312" height="2704" />\r\n\r\nOyster gardeners first attend a special workshop where they learn all the details of the program and build their own oyster habitats. Later, they receive oyster shells covered with live spat (juvenile oysters), which they place into their habitats and deploy from their docks, beginning the care and data collection process. To ensure the greatest probability of success, the oyster spat used in the Oyster Gardening project are spawned from a local brood stock near Sebastian, FL. Their spawning takes place at the Florida Oceanographic Society, in a hatchery dedicated to the reproduction of the Eastern Oyster. Using a local population of oysters from Brevard County to parent these oyster spat will keep future generations of oysters in restored populations genetically similar to those that once made up the areaâs original population.\r\n\r\n[gallery columns="5" link="file" ids="656,658,654,603,1076"]', 'Oyster Gardening Program', '', 'inherit', 'closed', 'open', '', '899-revision-v1', '', '', '2014-12-22 15:12:36', '2014-12-22 15:12:36', '', 899, 'http://brevardoystergardens.org/899-revision-v1/', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
