(1233, 5, '2014-12-22 14:32:03', '2014-12-22 14:32:03', '[gallery link="file" columns="5" ids="1207,1199,1205,1201,1200"]\r\n\r\nTheÂ Brevard Oyster Gardening project, launched by Brevard Zoo in partnership with the Brevard County Natural Resources Management Office, is encouraging the community to get involved with the process of repairing damages to the lagoon. Inspired by the oyster reef restoration work that Brevard Zoo has been doing with UCF in Mosquito Lagoon, the Oyster Gardening Project has expanded reef restoration intoÂ the more challenging Brevard County portion of theÂ Indian River Lagoon by first identifying areas with high rates of oyster survivability and recruitment that are good candidate locations for Â reef restoration projects. Oysters grown through the Oyster Gardening program are then used to populate Brevard County restoration reefs, the first of which were built in the fall of 2014. Compared to the Volusia County portion of the lagoon where the Oyster Mats program operates, Â oyster populations in Brevard County have suffered such a great decline that both oyster habitat restoration and oyster reintroduction are necessary, which is what the Oyster Gardening Program has been designed to address...\r\n\r\n<img class="alignnone  wp-image-716" alt="Home7" src="http://brevardoystergardens.org/wp-content/uploads/2014/04/Home7.jpg" width="974" height="773" />\r\n\r\nIn order to grow oysters and collect the necessary data for reef placement, the Brevard County Commissioners funded the project with $150,000 to supply a small staff and provide the necessary equipment to train volunteers in Brevard County to become âoyster gardeners.â The project relies entirely onÂ <a href="https://mapalist.com/Public/pm.aspx?mapid=435233" target="_blank">these volunteers</a>Â living along the shores of the Indian River Lagoon who agree to hang oyster habitats from their docks and then care for and monitor their oysters to collect data on the growth, survivability, and recruitment of oysters in their area, all of which gets entered into a database on a weekly basis for a period of about six Â months.\r\n\r\n<img class="alignnone  wp-image-596" alt="Oysters_Kiwanis Park 36" src="http://brevardoystergardens.org/wp-content/uploads/2014/03/Oysters_Kiwanis-Park-361.jpg" width="3312" height="2704" />\r\n\r\nOyster gardeners first attend a special workshop where they learn all the details of the program and build their own oyster habitats. Later, they receive oyster shells covered with live spat (juvenile oysters), which they place into their habitats and deploy from their docks, beginning the care and data collection process. To ensure the greatest probability of success, the oyster spat used in the Oyster Gardening project are spawned from a local brood stock near Sebastian, FL. Their spawning takes place at the Florida Oceanographic Society, in a hatchery dedicated to the reproduction of the Eastern Oyster. Using a local population of oysters from Brevard County to parent these oyster spat will keep future generations of oysters in restored populations genetically similar to those that once made up the areaâs original population.\r\n\r\n[gallery columns="5" link="file" ids="656,658,654,603,1076"]', 'Oyster Gardening Program', '', 'inherit', 'closed', 'open', '', '899-revision-v1', '', '', '2014-12-22 14:32:03', '2014-12-22 14:32:03', '', 899, 'http://brevardoystergardens.org/899-revision-v1/', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
