(1391, 5, '2015-09-17 15:57:28', '2015-09-17 15:57:28', 'OYSTER GARDENING TRAINING FOR 2015 IS COMPLETE. THE NEXT ROUND OF TRAINING WILL BEGIN IN SUMMER 2016.\r\n\r\n<em>(Please joinÂ our <a href="http://eepurl.com/bzBu0X" target="_blank">waiting list</a> to receiveÂ e-mail notification when our 2016 schedule is released.)</em>\r\n\r\nOyster Gardening workshops are <b>only for qualified individuals</b> and require reservations in advance. If you are approved for a workshop, we will provide all necessary supplies, so just plan to arrive 15 minutes early for sign-in, then stay throughout the entirety of the two-hour workshop. Â Oyster Gardening is a great activity to get the whole family involved with at home, but please note that gardening workshops are primarily directed toward adults...\r\n\r\n<img class="alignnone  wp-image-607" src="http://brevardoystergardens.org/wp-content/uploads/2014/03/Oysters_Kiwanis-Park-221-1024x676.jpg" alt="" width="740" height="486" />\r\n\r\n<b><span style="text-decoration: underline;">HOW DO I QUALIFY FOR A WORKSHOP?</span></b>\r\n\r\nOnly those who are qualified to be either an Oyster Gardener or Oyster Buddy may attend an Oyster Gardening workshop. The requirements for both designations are as follows:\r\n\r\n<b>Oyster Gardener</b>\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>Has a dock on the Â Indian River Lagoon in Brevard County. Community docks for homeowners associations and condos can also be eligible, but check out these special <a href="http://brevardoystergardens.org/wp-content/uploads/2014/06/Community-Docks-Guidelines.docx">guidelines</a> first.</li>\r\n	<li>Can commit one to two hours of time per week to cleaning and monitoring oyster habitats and entering findings into a database</li>\r\n	<li>Not planning to be out of town for extended periods of time (more than two weeks) over the next six to seven months</li>\r\n	<li>Can lift 30 lbs</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<b>Oyster Buddy</b>\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>Able to temporarily fill in for traveling or sick Oyster Gardeners by committing one to two hours per week to maintaining and monitoring their habitats for them</li>\r\n	<li>Has access to a reliable means of transportation to Oyster Gardening sites</li>\r\n	<li>Can lift 30 lbs</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<img class="alignnone  wp-image-718" src="http://brevardoystergardens.org/wp-content/uploads/2014/04/Home9.jpg" alt="Home9" width="707" height="643" />\r\n\r\n<b>IF YOU MEET THE REQUIREMENTS</b> to be either an Oyster Gardener or Oyster Buddy, please visit our <a href="http://brevardoystergardens.org/volunteer/" target="_blank">Volunteer</a><a href="http://brevardoystergardens.org/get-involved/">Â </a>page to sign upÂ for an upcoming oyster gardening workshop. <em>Only one registration is necessary per family/group.Â </em>', 'Oyster Gardening Workshops', '', 'inherit', 'closed', 'open', '', '903-revision-v1', '', '', '2015-09-17 15:57:28', '2015-09-17 15:57:28', '', 903, 'http://brevardoystergardens.org/903-revision-v1/', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
(1392, 5, '2015-09-17 16:01:17', '2015-09-17 16:01:17', 'Since 2005, Brevard Zoo, in partnership with UCF, has been using special oyster restoration mats to rebuild oyster reef habitat in suitable areas of Mosquito Lagoon, a region of the Indian River Lagoon located in Volusia County that is part of theÂ <a href="http://www.nps.gov/cana/index.htm" target="_blank"><span style="text-decoration: underline;">Canaveral National Seashore</span></a>...\r\n\r\n<img class="alignnone  wp-image-893" src="http://brevardoystergardens.org/wp-content/uploads/2014/03/Oysters13.jpg" alt="" width="4206" height="2880" />\r\n\r\nThe restoration process begins by raking down and leveling layers of accumulated dead oysters, known as dead margins, at former oyster reef sites. Once the site has been leveled to the proper intertidal height, the next step is anchoring down oyster mats, upon which new oysters can have a permanent home without the possibility of future disturbance. The oyster mats are laid out like a patchwork quilt and are connected and anchored using concrete doughnuts. Within one year, a single oyster mat will become home to an average of 97 new baby oysters.\r\n\r\n<img class="alignnone size-full wp-image-56" src="http://brevardoystergardens.org/wp-content/uploads/2014/03/OysterMat41.png" alt="OysterMat4" width="458" height="382" />\r\n\r\nThe oyster mats themselves are made from sections of aquaculture grade mesh containing 36 empty oyster shells attached with zip ties. The mats are placed on the estuary floor in order to provide a hard substrate for free-floating oyster larvae to attach to so that they can begin to build a new reef. Since oysters are a gregarious species, meaning they like to live in groups, the placement of shells in these areas attracts the larvae, which can detect the calcium carbonate in the shells of other oysters. And the mats are such an effective substrate that, not only will they withstand disruption from boats, but they will even endure hurricanes.Â For that reason, use of oyster mats is a means of accomplishing the permanent restoration of oyster reefs in the northern portion of the Indian River Lagoon.\r\n\r\n<img class="alignnone  wp-image-55" src="http://brevardoystergardens.org/wp-content/uploads/2014/03/OysterMat31.png" alt="OysterMat3" width="738" height="468" />\r\n\r\nSo far, the Oyster Mats project has used over 41,000 mats to help build 73 restored reefs.Â The project is almost exclusively based on the efforts of more than 43,000 volunteers from all across Florida who are responsible for virtually every aspect of the project, from cutting and assembling mats to drilling shells, transporting mats to restoration sites and installing mats on restoration reefs.\r\n\r\nClick link to read the <a href="http://brevardoystergardens.org/wp-content/uploads/2015/02/2014-Oyster-Mats-Annual-Report.pdf" target="_blank">Oyster Mats 2014 Annual Report</a>.', 'Oyster Mats Details', '', 'inherit', 'closed', 'open', '', '953-revision-v1', '', '', '2015-09-17 16:01:17', '2015-09-17 16:01:17', '', 953, 'http://brevardoystergardens.org/953-revision-v1/', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
(1393, 5, '2015-09-17 16:01:54', '2015-09-17 16:01:54', 'Since 2005, Brevard Zoo, in partnership with UCF, has been using special oyster restoration mats to rebuild oyster reef habitat in suitable areas of Mosquito Lagoon, a region of the Indian River Lagoon located in Volusia County that is part of theÂ <a href="http://www.nps.gov/cana/index.htm" target="_blank">Canaveral National Seashore</a>...\r\n\r\n<img class="alignnone  wp-image-893" src="http://brevardoystergardens.org/wp-content/uploads/2014/03/Oysters13.jpg" alt="" width="4206" height="2880" />\r\n\r\nThe restoration process begins by raking down and leveling layers of accumulated dead oysters, known as dead margins, at former oyster reef sites. Once the site has been leveled to the proper intertidal height, the next step is anchoring down oyster mats, upon which new oysters can have a permanent home without the possibility of future disturbance. The oyster mats are laid out like a patchwork quilt and are connected and anchored using concrete doughnuts. Within one year, a single oyster mat will become home to an average of 97 new baby oysters.\r\n\r\n<img class="alignnone size-full wp-image-56" src="http://brevardoystergardens.org/wp-content/uploads/2014/03/OysterMat41.png" alt="OysterMat4" width="458" height="382" />\r\n\r\nThe oyster mats themselves are made from sections of aquaculture grade mesh containing 36 empty oyster shells attached with zip ties. The mats are placed on the estuary floor in order to provide a hard substrate for free-floating oyster larvae to attach to so that they can begin to build a new reef. Since oysters are a gregarious species, meaning they like to live in groups, the placement of shells in these areas attracts the larvae, which can detect the calcium carbonate in the shells of other oysters.Â And the mats are such an effective substrate that, not only will they withstand disruption from boats, but they will even endure hurricanes.Â For that reason, use of oyster mats is a means of accomplishing the permanent restoration of oyster reefs in the northern portion of the Indian River Lagoon.\r\n\r\n<img class="alignnone  wp-image-55" src="http://brevardoystergardens.org/wp-content/uploads/2014/03/OysterMat31.png" alt="OysterMat3" width="738" height="468" />\r\n\r\nSo far, the Oyster Mats project has used over 41,000 mats to help build 73 restored reefs.Â The project is almost exclusively based on the efforts of more than 43,000 volunteers from all across Florida who are responsible for virtually every aspect of the project, from cutting and assembling mats to drilling shells, transporting mats to restoration sites and installing mats on restoration reefs.\r\n\r\nClick link to read the <a href="http://brevardoystergardens.org/wp-content/uploads/2015/02/2014-Oyster-Mats-Annual-Report.pdf" target="_blank">Oyster Mats 2014 Annual Report</a>.', 'Oyster Mats Program', '', 'inherit', 'closed', 'open', '', '52-revision-v1', '', '', '2015-09-17 16:01:54', '2015-09-17 16:01:54', '', 52, 'http://brevardoystergardens.org/52-revision-v1/', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
(1520, 5, '2016-05-30 16:00:34', '2016-05-30 16:00:34', '[gallery columns="5" link="file" ids="626,1053,54,622,1057"]\r\n\r\n<strong>Itâs mat deployment season!</strong> We are planning to start workshops again in the fall, contingent upon grant funding approval. Please join us to restore oyster reefs in Mosquito Lagoon and/or build reefs in Brevard County. To learn more and sign-up, please visit our <a href="http://brevardoystergardens.org/volunteer/">Volunteer</a> page. Hope to work with you soon!\r\n\r\n\r\n--------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------\r\n\r\n\r\nMat-making workshops, hosted at various parks throughout Brevard County, are free and open to the public from 10:00 a.m. to 11:30 a.m., or until materials are depleted. All ages are welcome, materials will be provided for you, and no reservation is required. During the workshop, youâll be learning about our restoration projects and creating oyster mats by attaching oyster shells to squares of aquaculture mesh using zip ties. It usually takes between 15 and 20 minutes to make one oyster mat, and the oyster shells can be dusty, so try to wear clothing that you donât mind getting a bit dirty. Work gloves are not required, but if you''d prefer to wear them, feel free to bring your own pair. \r\n <strong> Oyster Mat Workshops will pick back up in the fall, please check back later or subscribe to our <a href="http://brevardoystergardens.org/contact-us/">newsletter</a>.</strong>\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n<iframe src="https://www.youtube.com/embed/PRYDDRHTlVI" width="853" height="480" frameborder="0" allowfullscreen="allowfullscreen"></iframe>\r\n\r\nCheck out these oyster <a href="http://brevardoystergardens.org/wp-content/uploads/2015/05/HowtoHandoutKB.pdf" target="_blank">mat-making instructions</a>.', 'Help Make Oyster Mats', '', 'inherit', 'closed', 'open', '', '895-revision-v1', '', '', '2016-05-30 16:00:34', '2016-05-30 16:00:34', '', 895, 'http://brevardoystergardens.org/895-revision-v1/', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
